\id MAT Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Matthew
\mt1 The Holy Gospel of Jesus Christ according to Matthew.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 \sc The\sc* book of the generation of \sc Jesus\sc* Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham. \f + \fr 1:1 \ft This Gospel is most solemnly sung in some Churches after Matins upon Christmas day. As also it is the Gospel of the Conception, Nativity, and Presentation of our B. Lady: because here is declared the pedigree of her also.\f*
\v 2 Abraham begat Isaac, And Isaac begat Jacob. And Jacob begat Judas and his brethren:
\v 3 And Judas begat Phares and Zaram of Thamar. And Phares begat Esron. And Esron begat Aram.
\v 4 And Aram begat Aminadab. And Aminadab begat Naasson. And Naasson begat Salmon.
\v 5 And Salmon begat Booz of Rahab. And Booz begat Obed of Ruth. And Obed begat Jesse.
\v 6 And Jesse begat David the king. And David the king begat Salomon of her that was the wife of Urias.
\v 7 And Salomon begat Roboam. And Roboam begat Abia. And Abia begat Asa.
\v 8 And Asa begat Josaphat. And Josaphat begat Joram. And Joram begat Ozias.
\v 9 And Ozias begat Joatham. And Joatham begat Achaz. And Achaz begat Ezechias.
\v 10 And Ezechias begat Manasses. And Manasses begat Amon. And Amon begat Josias.
\v 11 And Josias begat Jechonias and his brethren in the Transmigration of Babylon.
\v 12 And after the Transmigration of Babylon, Jechonias begat Salathiel. And Salathiel begat Zorobabel.
\v 13 And Zorobabel begat Abiud. And Abiud begat Eliacim. And Eliacim begat Azor.
\v 14 And Azor begat Sadoc. And Sadoc begat Achim. And Achim begat Eliud.
\v 15 And Eliud begat Eleazar. And Eleazar begat Mathan. And Mathan begat Jacob.
\v 16 And Jacob begat Joseph the husband of \sc Mary\sc*: of whom was born \sc Jesus\sc*, who is called \sc Christ\sc*. \f + \fr 1:16 \ft de qua.\f*
\v 17 Therefore all the generations from Abraham unto David, fourteen generations. And from David to the Transmigration of Babylon, fourteen generations. And from the Transmigration of Babylon unto \sc Christ\sc*, fourteen generations.
\v 18 And the generation of \sc Christ\sc* was in this wise. When his mother \sc Mary\sc* was spoused to Joseph, before they came together, she was found to be with child, by the Holy Ghost. \f + \fr 1:18 \ft The Gospel upon Christmas eve. and Upon S. Joseph's day the 19. of March.\f*
\v 19 Whereupon Joseph her husband for that he was a just man, & would not put her to open shame: was minded secretly to dismiss her. \f + \fr 1:19 \ft This word just, sounding that a man is just indeed, & not only so imputed, Protestants translate, Righteous in this and diverse other places.\f*
\v 20 But as he was thus thinking, behold the Angel of our Lord appeared to him in sleep saying: Joseph son of David, fear not to take \sc Mary\sc* thy wife, for that which is born in her, is of the Holy Ghost.
\v 21 And she shall bring forth a Son: and thou shalt call his name \sc Jesus\sc*. For he shall save his people from their sins. \f + \fr 1:21 \ft JESUS an Hebrew word, in English SAVIOUR.\f*
\v 22 And all this was done that it might be fulfilled which our Lord spake by the Prophet saying.
\v 23 \add Behold a Virgin shall be with child, & bring forth a son, and they shall call his name Emmanuel,\add* which being interpreted is, God with us.
\v 24 And Joseph rising up from sleep, did as the Angel of our Lord commanded him, & took his wife.
\v 25 And he knew her not till she brought forth her first born Son: & called his name \sc Jesus\sc*.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 \sc When Jesus\sc* therefore was born in Bethlehem of Juda in the days of Herod the king, behold there came Sages from the East to Jerusalem, \f + \fr 2:1 \ft The holy feast of the Epiphany called Twelfth -day the 6. of January. Upon which day this is the Gospel.\f*
\v 2 Saying, where is he that is born King of the Jews? For we have seen his star in the East, and are come to adore him.
\v 3 And Herod the king Hearing this, was troubled, & all Jerusalem with him.
\v 4 And assembling together all the high Priests and the Scribes of the people, he inquired of them where Christ should be born.
\v 5 But they said to him: In Bethlehem of Juda. For so it is written by the Prophet:
\v 6 \add And thou Bethlehem the land of Juda, art not the least among the Princes of Juda: for out of thee shall come forth the Captain that shall rule my people Israel.\add*
\v 7 Then Herod secretly calling the Sages, learned diligently of them the time of the star which appeared to them;
\v 8 and sending them into Bethlehem, said: Go, & inquire diligently of the child; and when you shall find him, make report to me, that I also may come and adore him.
\v 9 Who having heard the king, went their way; and behold the star which they had seen in the East, went before them, until it came and stood over, where the child was.
\v 10 And seeing the star they rejoiced with exceeding great joy.
\v 11 And entering into the house, they found the child with \sc Mary\sc* his mother, & falling down adored him; and opening their treasures, they offered to him gifts: gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
\v 12 And having received an answer in sleep that they should not return to Herod, they went back another way into their country.
\v 13 And after they were departed, Behold an Angel of our Lord appeared in sleep to Joseph, saying: Arise, & take the child and his mother, and fly into Ægypt; and be there until I shall tell thee. For it will come to pass that Herod will seek the child to destroy him. \f + \fr 2:13 \ft The Gospel of Childermas day.\f*
\v 14 Who arose, & took the child and his mother by night, and retired into Ægypt: and he was there until the death of Herod:
\v 15 that it might be fulfilled which was spoken of our Lord by the Prophet, saying: \add Out of Ægypt have I called my Son.\add*
\v 16 Then Herod perceiving that he was deluded by the Sages, was exceeding angry; and sending murdered all the men children that were in Bethlehem, & in all the borders thereof, from two year old and under, according to the time which he had diligently sought out of the Sages. \f + \fr 2:16 \ft The Martyrdom of the holy innocents, whose holy-day\f*
\v 17 Then was fulfilled that which was spoken by Jeremy the Prophet saying:
\v 18 \add A voice in Rama was heard, crying out & much wailing: Rachel bewailing her children, & would not be comforted, because they are not.\add*
\v 19 But when Herod was dead, behold an Angel of our Lord appeared in sleep to Joseph in Ægypt. \f + \fr 2:19 \ft The Gospel on Twelfth eve.\f*
\v 20 saying: Arise, and take the child & his mother, and go into the land of Israel. For they are dead that sought the life of the child.
\v 21 Who arose, & took the child and his mother, and came into the land of Israel.
\v 22 But hearing that Archelaus reigned in Jewry for Herod his father, he feared to go thither: and being warned in sleep retired into the quarters of Galilee.
\v 23 And coming he dwelt in a city called Nazareth: that it might be fulfilled which was said by the Prophets: That he shall be called a Nazarite.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* in those days cometh John the Baptist preaching in the desert of Jewry, \f + \fr 3:1 \ft THE SECOND part of this Gospel, Of the Preparation that was made to the manifestation of Christ\f*
\v 2 & saying: Do penance: for the Kingdom of Heaven is at hand.
\v 3 For this is he that was spoken of by Esay the Prophet, saying: \add A voice of one crying in the desert, prepare ye the way of our Lord, make straight his paths.\add*
\v 4 And the said John had his garment of camels' hair, and a girdle of a skin about his loins: and his meat was locusts & wild honey.
\v 5 Then went forth to him Jerusalem and all Jewry, and all the country about Jordan:
\v 6 & were baptized of him in Jordan, confessing their sins.
\v 7 And seeing many of the Pharisees and Sadducees coming to his Baptism, he said to them. Ye viper's brood, who hath shewed you to flee from the wrath to come?
\v 8 Yield therefore fruit worthy of penance.
\v 9 And delight not to say within yourselves, we have Abraham to our father. For I tell you that God is able of these stones to raise up children to Abraham.
\v 10 For now the axe is put to the root of the trees. Every tree therefore that doth not yield good fruit, shall be cut down, & cast into the fire. \f + \fr 3:10 \ft It is not only damnable, to do ill: but also, not to do good. Aug. Ser. 6. de temp.\f*
\v 11 I indeed baptize you in water unto penance, but he that shall come after me, is stronger than I, whose shoes I am not worthy to bear, he shall baptize you in the Holy Ghost & fire.
\v 12 Whose fan is in his hand, and he shall clean purge his floor: and he will gather his wheat into the barn, but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire.
\v 13 Then cometh \sc Jesus\sc* from Galilee to Jordan, unto John, to be baptized of him.
\v 14 But John stayed him, saying: I ought to be baptized of thee, and comest thou to me?
\v 15 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said to him: Suffer me for this time. For so it becometh us to fulfill all justice. Then he suffered him.
\v 16 And \sc Jesus\sc* being baptized, forthwith came out of the water: and lo the Heavens were opened to him: & he saw the Spirit of God descending as a dove, & coming upon him.
\v 17 And behold a voice from Heaven saying: This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 \sc Then Jesus\sc* was led of the Spirit into the desert, to be tempted of the devil. \f + \fr 4:1 \ft The Gospel upon the first Sunday in Lent.\f*
\v 2 And when he had fasted forty days and forty nights, afterward he was hungry.
\v 3 And the tempter approached and said to him: If thou be the Son of God, command that these stones be made bread.
\v 4 Who answered and said: It is written, \add Not in bread alone doth man live, but in every word that proceedeth from the mouth of God.\add*
\v 5 Then the devil took him up into the holy city, and set him upon the pinnacle of the Temple,
\v 6 and said to him: If thou be the Son of God, cast thyself down, for it is written: \add That he will give his Angels charge of thee, & in their hands shall they hold thee up, lest perhaps thou knock thy foot against a stone.\add*
\v 7 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him again: It is written, \add Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God.\add*
\v 8 Again the devil took him up into a very high mountain: and he shewed him all the kingdoms of the world, and the glory of them,
\v 9 and said to him: All these will I give thee, if falling down thou wilt adore me.
\v 10 Then \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Avaunt Satan; for it is written, \add The Lord thy God shalt thou adore, and him only shalt thou serve.\add*
\v 11 Then the devil left him; and behold Angels came, and ministered to him.
\v 12 And when \sc Jesus\sc* had heard that John was delivered up, he retired into Galilee : \f + \fr 4:12 \ft THE THIRD part of the Gospel, of Christ's manifesting himself by preaching, and that in Galilee.\f*
\v 13 and leaving the city Nazareth, came and dwelt in Capharnaum a sea town, in the borders of Zabulon & Nephthali;
\v 14 that it might be fulfilled which was said by Esay the Prophet.
\v 15 \add Land of Zabulon & land of Nephthali, the way of the sea beyond Jordan of Galilee, of the Gentiles:\add*
\v 16 \add the people that sat in darkness, hath seen great light:\add* & to them that sat in a country of the shadow of death, \add light is risen to them.\add*
\v 17 From that time \sc Jesus\sc* began to preach, and to say: Do penance, for the Kingdom of Heaven is at hand.
\v 18 And \sc Jesus\sc* walking by the sea of Galilee, saw two brethren, Simon who is called Peter, and Andrew his brother, casting a net into the sea (for they were fishers) \f + \fr 4:18 \ft The Gospel upon S. Andrew's day.\f*
\v 19 and he saith to them: Come ye after me, and I will make you to be fishers of men.
\v 20 But they incontinent leaving the nets, followed him.
\v 21 And going forward from thence, he saw other two brethren, James of Zebedee, and John his brother, in a ship with Zebedee their father, repairing their nets: and he called them.
\v 22 And they forthwith left their nets and father and followed him.
\v 23 And \sc Jesus\sc* went round about all Galilee, teaching in their Synagogues, & preaching the Gospel of the Kingdom: and healing every malady, and every infirmity, in the people.
\v 24 And the bruit of him went into all Syria, and they presented to him all that were ill at ease, diversely taken with diseases and torments, and such as were possest, and lunatics, and sick of the palsy, and he cured them:
\v 25 And much people followed him from Galilee, and Decapolis, and Jerusalem, and from Jury and from beyond Jordan.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 And seeing the multitudes, he went up into a mountain: and when he was set, his Disciples came unto him,
\v 2 and opening his mouth he taught them, saying.
\v 3 Blessed are the poor in spirit: for theirs is the Kingdom of Heaven. \f + \fr 5:3 \ft THE EIGHT Beatitudes: which are a part of the Catechism. The Gospel upon Allhallows' day, and upon the feasts of many Martyrs.\f*
\v 4 Blessed are the meek: for they shall possess the land.
\v 5 Blessed are they that mourn: for they shall be comforted.
\v 6 Blessed are they that hunger and thirst after justice: for they shall have their fill.
\v 7 Blessed are the merciful: for they shall obtain mercy.
\v 8 Blessed are the clean of heart: for they shall see God.
\v 9 Blessed are the peace-makers: for they shall be called the children of God.
\v 10 Blessed are they that suffer persecution for justice: for theirs is the Kingdom of Heaven.
\v 11 Blessed are ye when they shall revile you, and persecute you, & speak all that naught is against you, untruly, for my sake:
\v 12 be glad & rejoice, for your reward is very great in Heaven. For so they persecuted the Prophets, that were before you.
\v 13 You are the salt of the earth. \f + \fr 5:13 \ft The Gospel on the feasts of Doctors.\f*
\v 14 But if the salt leese his virtue, wherewith shall it be salted? It is good for nothing any more but to be cast forth, and to be trodden of men.
\v 15 You are the light of the world. A city cannot be hid, situated on a mountain.
\v 16 Neither do men light a candle and put it under a bushel, but upon a candlestick, that it may shine to all that are in the house.
\v 17 So let your light shine before men, that they may see your good works, and glorify your Father which is in Heaven.
\v 18 Do not think that I am come to break the Law, or the Prophets. I am not come to break, but to fulfill.
\v 19 For assuredly I say unto you, till Heaven and earth pass, one jot, or one tittle shall not pass of the Law, till all be fulfilled.
\v 20 He therefore that shall break one of these least commandments, and shall so teach men, shall be called the least in the Kingdom of Heaven. But he that shall do and teach, he shall be called great in the Kingdom of Heaven.
\v 21 For I tell you, that unless your justice abound more than that of the Scribes and Pharisees, you shall not enter into the Kingdom of Heaven. \f + \fr 5:21 \ft The Gospel upon the fifth Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 22 You have heard that it was said to them of old: Thou shalt not kill. And whoso killeth, shall be in danger of judgement.
\v 23 But I say to you, that whosoever is angry with his brother, shall be in danger of judgment. And whosoever shall say to his brother, Raca, shall be in danger of a council. And whosoever shall say, Thou fool, shall be guilty of the Hell of fire.
\v 24 If therefore thou offer thy gift at the Altar, and there thou remember that thy brother hath ought against thee;
\v 25 leave there thy offering before the Altar, and go first to be reconciled to thy brother: and then coming thou shalt offer thy gift.
\v 26 Be at agreement with thy adversary betimes, whiles thou art in the way with him; lest perhaps the adversary deliver thee to the judge, and the judge deliver thee to the officer, and thou be cast into prison. \f + \fr 5:26 \ft This Prison is taken of very ancient Fathers, for Purgatory: namely S. Cypr. ep. 52. ad Anton. nu. 6.\f*
\v 27 Amen I say to thee, thou shalt not go out from thence till thou repay the last farthing.
\v 28 You have heard that it was said to them of old: Thou shalt not commit adultery.
\v 29 But I say to you, that whosoever shall see a woman to lust after her, hath already committed adultery with her in his heart.
\v 30 And if thy right eye scandalize thee, pluck it out, & cast it from thee. For it is expedient for thee that one of thy limbs perish, rather than thy whole body be cast into hell.
\v 31 And if thy right hand scandalize thee, cut it off, and cast it from thee: for it is expedient for thee that one of thy limbs perish rather than that thy whole body go into Hell.
\v 32 It was said also, whosoever shall dismiss his wife, let him give her a bill of divorcement.
\v 33 But I say to you, whosoever shall dismiss his wife, excepting the cause of fornication, maketh her to commit adultery: And he that shall marry her that is dismissed; committeth adultery.
\v 34 Again you have heard that it was said to them of old, Thou shalt not commit perjury: but thou shall perform thy oaths to our Lord.
\v 35 But I say to you not to swear at all: neither by heaven, because it is the throne of God: neither by the earth, because it is the foot-stool of his feet: neither by Jerusalem, because it is the city of the great King.
\v 36 Neither shalt thou swear by thy head, because thou canst not make one hair white or black.
\v 37 Let your talk be yea, yea: no, no: and that which is over & above these, is of evil.
\v 38 You have heard that it was said, An eye for an eye, and a tooth for a tooth.
\v 39 But I say to you not to resist evil: but if one strike thee on thy right cheek, turn to him also the other:
\v 40 and to him that will contend with thee in judgement, and take away thy coat, let go thy cloak also unto him.
\v 41 and whosoever will force thee one mile, go with him other twain.
\v 42 He that asketh of thee, give to him: and to him that would borrow of thee, turn not away.
\v 43 You have heard that it was said, Thou shalt love thy neighbour, & hate thine enemy. \f + \fr 5:43 \ft The Gospel upon the Friday after Ashwednesday.\f* \f + \fr 5:43 \ft So taught the Pharisees, not the Law.\f*
\v 44 But I say to you, love your enemies, do good to them that hate you: and pray for them that persecute and abuse you:
\v 45 that you may be the children of your father which is in heaven, who maketh his sun to rise upon good & bad, and raineth upon just and unjust. \f + \fr 5:45 \ft We see then that the temporal prosperity of persons and countries is no sign of better men or truer religion.\f*
\v 46 For if you love them that love you, what reward shall you have? Do not also the Publicans this?
\v 47 And if you salute your brethren only, what do you more, do not also the Heathen this?
\v 48 Be you perfect therefore, as also your heavenly Father is perfect.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 \sc Take\sc* good heed that you do not your justice before men, to be seen of them: otherwise reward you shall not have with your father which is in heaven.
\v 2 Therefore when thou doest an alms-deed, sound not a trumpet before thee, as the Hypocrites do in the Synagogues and in the streets, that they may be honoured of men: Amen I say to you, they have received their reward. \f + \fr 6:2 \ft The first work of justice.\f*
\v 3 But when thou doest an alms-deed, let not thy left hand know what thy right hand doeth:
\v 4 that thy alms-deed may be in secret, and thy father which seeth in secret, will repay thee.
\v 5 And when ye pray, you shall not be as the hypocrites, that love to stand and pray in the Synagogues & corners of the streets, that they may be seen of men: Amen I say to you, they have received their reward. \f + \fr 6:5 \ft The second work of justice.\f*
\v 6 But thou when thou shalt pray, enter into thy chamber, and having shut the door, pray to thy father in secret: and thy father which seeth in secret, will repay thee.
\v 7 And when you are praying, speak not much, as the Heathen. For they think that in their much-speaking they may be heard.
\v 8 Be not you therefore like to them, for your father knoweth what is needful for you, before you ask him.
\v 9 Thus therefore shall you pray. \add \sc Our Father\sc* which art in heaven, sanctified be thy name.\add* \f + \fr 6:9 \ft The PATER NOSTER.\f*
\v 10 \add Let thy Kingdom come. Thy will be done, as in heaven, in earth also.\add*
\v 11 \add Give us today our \add* \add supersubstantial bread.\add* \f + \fr 6:11 \ft In S. Luke, the Latin is, Panem quotidianum, daily bread, the Greek being indifferent to both, τὸν ἐπιούσιον.\f*
\v 12 \add And forgive us our debts, as we also forgive our debtors,\add*
\v 13 \add And lead us not into tentation. But deliver us from evil. Amen.\add*
\v 14 For if you will forgive men their offences, your heavenly father will forgive you also your offences.
\v 15 But if you will not forgive men, neither will your father forgive you your offences.
\v 16 And when you fast, be not as the hypocrites, sad. For they disfigure their faces, that they may appear unto men to fast. Amen I say to you, that they have received their reward. \f + \fr 6:16 \ft The third work of justice.\f*
\v 17 But thou when thou doest fast, anoint thy head, and wash thy face: \f + \fr 6:17 \ft The Gospel upon Ashwednesday.\f*
\v 18 that thou appear not to men to fast, but to thy father which is in secret: and thy father which seeth in secret, will repay thee.
\v 19 Heap not up to yourselves treasures on the earth: where the rust and moth do corrupt, & where thieves dig through and steal.
\v 20 But heap up to yourselves treasures in heaven: where neither the rust nor moth doth corrupt, and where thieves do not dig through nor steal.
\v 21 For where thy treasure is, there is thy heart also.
\v 22 The candle of thy body is thine eye. If thine eye be simple, thy whole body shall be lightsome.
\v 23 But if thine eye be naught: thy whole body shall be darksome. If then the light that is in thee, be darkness: the darkness itself how great shall it be?
\v 24 No man can serve two masters. For either he will hate the one, and love the other: or he will sustain the one, and contemn the other. You cannot serve God and Mammon. \f + \fr 6:24 \ft The Gospel on the 14 Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 25 Therefore I say to you, be not careful for your life, what you shall eat, neither for your body what raiment you shall put on. Is not the life more than the meat: and the body more than the raiment?
\v 26 Behold the fowls of the air, that they sow not, neither reap, nor gather into barns: and your heavenly father feedeth them.
\v 27 And which of you by caring, can add to his stature one cubit?
\v 28 And for raiment why are you careful? Consider the lilies of the field how they grow: they labour not, neither do they spin.
\v 29 But I say to you, that neither Salomon in all his glory was arrayed as one of these.
\v 30 And if the grass of the field, which today is, and tomorrow is cast into the oven, God doth so clothe: how much more you, O ye of very small faith?
\v 31 Be not careful therefore, saying, what shall we eat, or what shall we drink, or wherewith shall we be covered?
\v 32 for all these things the Heathen do seek after. For your father knoweth that you need all these things. \f + \fr 6:32 \ft They seek temporal things only, and that not of the true God, but of their idols, or by their own industry.\f*
\v 33 Seek therefore first the Kingdom of God, and the justice of him, and all these things shall be given you besides.
\v 34 Be not careful therefore for the morrow; for the morrow day will be careful for itself. Sufficient for the day is the evil thereof.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 \sc Judge\sc* not, that you be not judged.
\v 2 For in what judgement you judge, you shall be judged: and in what measure you mete, it shall be measured to you again.
\v 3 And why seest thou the mote that is in thy brother's eye: and the beam that is in thine own eye thou seest not?
\v 4 Or how sayest thou to thy brother: Let me cast out the mote of thine eye; and behold a beam is in thine own eye?
\v 5 Hypocrite, cast out first the beam out of thine own eye; and then shalt thou see to cast out the mote out of thy brother's eye.
\v 6 Give not that which is holy to dogs: neither cast ye your pearls before swine, lest perhaps they tread them with their feet, & turning, all to tear you.
\v 7 Ask, and it shall be given you: seek, and you shall find, knock, & it shall be opened to you.
\v 8 For every one that asketh, receiveth: and that seeketh, findeth: and to him that knocketh, it shall be opened.
\v 9 Or what man is there of you, whom if his child shall ask bread, will he reach him a stone?
\v 10 Or if he shall ask him fish, will he reach him a serpent?
\v 11 If you then being naught, know how to give good gifts to your children: how much more will your Father which is in Heaven, give good things to them that ask him? \f + \fr 7:11 \ft These good things are grace and all spiritual gifts, and what soever pertaineth to the health of the soul.\f*
\v 12 All things therefore whatsoever you will that men do to you, do you also to them. For this is the Law and the Prophets.
\v 13 Enter ye by the narrow gate: because broad is the gate, and large is the way that leadeth to perdition, and many there be that enter by it.
\v 14 How narrow is the gate, and strait is the way that leadeth to life: & few there are that find it!
\v 15 Take ye great heed of false Prophets, which come to you in the clothing of sheep, but inwardly are ravening wolves. \f + \fr 7:15 \ft The Gospel on the 7. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 16 By their fruits you shall know them. Do men gather grapes of thorns, or figs of thistles?
\v 17 Even so every good tree yieldeth good fruits, and the evil tree yieldeth evil fruits.
\v 18 Agood tree cannot yield evil fruits, neither an evil tree yield good fruits.
\v 19 Every tree that yieldeth not good fruit, shall be cut down, and shall be cast into fire.
\v 20 Therefore by their fruits you shall know them.
\v 21 Not every one that sayeth to me, Lord, Lord, shall enter into the Kingdom of Heaven: but he that doth the will of my Father which is in Heaven, he shall enter into the Kingdom of Heaven.
\v 22 Many shall say to me in that day: Lord, Lord, have not we prophesied in thy name, and in thy name cast out devils, and in thy name wrought many miracles?
\v 23 And then I will confess unto them, That I never knew you: depart from me you that work iniquity.
\v 24 Every one therefore that heareth these words, and doeth them, shall be likened to a wise man that built his house upon a rock,
\v 25 and the rain fell, and the floods came, and the winds blew, and they beat against that house, and it fell not, for it was founded upon a rock.
\v 26 And every one that heareth these my words, and doeth them not, shall be like a foolish man that built his house upon the sand.
\v 27 and the rain fell, and the floods came, and the winds blew, and they beat against that house, and it fell, & the fall thereof was great.
\v 28 And it came to pass, when \sc Jesus\sc* had fully ended these words, the multitude were in admiration upon his doctrine.
\v 29 For he was teaching them as having power, and not as their Scribes and Pharisees.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when he was come down from the mountain, great multitudes followed him: \f + \fr 8:1 \ft The Gospel on the 3. Sunday after the Epiphany.\f*
\v 2 And behold a Leper came and adored him saying: Lord, if thou wilt, thou canst make me clean.
\v 3 And \sc Jesus\sc* stretching forth his hand, touched him, saying: I will. Be thou made clean. And forthwith, his leprosy was made clean.
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: See thou tell nobody: but go, shew thyself to the Priest, and offer the gift which Moyses commanded for a testimony to them.
\v 5 And when he was entered into Capharnaum, there came to him a Centurion, beseeching him, \f + \fr 8:5 \ft The Gospel upon the Thursday after Ashwednesday. And also in Mass for the sick.\f*
\v 6 and saying: Lord my boy lieth at home sick of the palsy, and is sore tormented.
\v 7 And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: I will come, and cure him.
\v 8 And the Centurion making answer, said: Lord, I am not worthy that thou shouldest enter under my roof: but only say the word, & my boy shall be healed.
\v 9 For I also am a man subject to authority, having under me soldiers; and I say to this go, and he goeth, and to another, come, and he cometh; and to my servant, do this, and he doeth it.
\v 10 And \sc Jesus\sc* hearing this, marveled: and said to them that followed him: Amen I say to you, I have not found so great faith in Israel.
\v 11 And I say to you that many shall come from the East and West, and shall sit down with Abraham, and Isaac, & Jacob in the Kingdom of Heaven:
\v 12 but the children of the Kingdom shall be cast out into the exterior darkness: there shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
\v 13 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to the Centurion: Go, and as thou hast believed, be it done to thee. And the boy was healed in the same hour.
\v 14 And when \sc Jesus\sc* was come into Peter's house, he saw his wife's mother laid, and in a fit of a fever:
\v 15 and he touched her hand, and the fever left her, and she arose, and ministered to him.
\v 16 And when evening was come, they brought to him many that had devils: and he cast out the spirits with a word: and all that were ill at ease he cured:
\v 17 that it might be fulfilled, which was spoken, by Esay the Prophet, saying: \add He took our infirmities, and bare our diseases.\add*
\v 18 And \sc Jesus\sc* seeing great multitudes about him, commanded to go beyond the water.
\v 19 And a certain Scribe came, and said to him: Master, I will follow thee whithersoever thou shalt go.
\v 20 And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: The foxes have holes, and the fowls of the air nests: but the Son of man hath not where to lay his head.
\v 21 And another of his Disciples said to him: Lord, permit me first to go and bury my father.
\v 22 But \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Follow me, and let the dead bury the dead.
\v 23 And when he entered into the boat, his Disciples followed him: \f + \fr 8:23 \ft The Gospel on the 4. Sunday after the Epiphany.\f*
\v 24 and lo a great tempest arose in the sea, so that the boat was covered with waves, but he slept.
\v 25 And they came to him, and raised him, saying: Lord, save us, we perish.
\v 26 And he saith to them: Why are you fearful, O ye of little faith? Then rising up he commanded the winds, and the sea, and there ensued a great calm.
\v 27 Moreover the men marveled, saying: What an one is this, for the winds and the sea obey him.
\v 28 And when he was come beyond the water, into the country of the Gerasens, there met him two that had devils, coming forth out of the sepulchres, exceeding fierce, so that none could pass by that way.
\v 29 And behold they cried saying: What is between us & thee \sc Jesus\sc* the Son of God? art thou come hither to torment us before the time.
\v 30 And there was not far from them an herd of many swine feeding.
\v 31 And the devils besought him saying: If thou cast us out, send us into the herd of swine.
\v 32 And he said to them: Go. But they going forth went into the swine, and behold the whole herd went with a violence, headlong into the sea: and they died in the waters.
\v 33 And the swineherds fled: and coming into the city, told all, and of them that had been possessed of devils.
\v 34 And behold the whole city went out to meet \sc Jesus\sc*, and when they saw him, they besought him that he would pass from their quarters.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* entering into a boat, he passed over the water, and came into his own city. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 18. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 2 And behold they brought to him one sick of the palsy lying in bed. And \sc Jesus\sc* seeing their faith, said to the sick of the palsy: Have a good heart son, thy sins are forgiven thee. \f + \fr 9:2 \ft We see that the faith of one helpeth to obtain for another.\f*
\v 3 And behold certain of the Scribes said within themselves: He blasphemeth.
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* seeing their thoughts, said: Wherefore think you evil in your hearts?
\v 5 Whether is easier, to say, thy sins are forgiven thee: or to say, arise and walk.
\v 6 But that you may know that the Son of man hath power in earth to forgive sins, (then said he to the sick of the palsy,) Arise, take up thy bed, and go into thy house.
\v 7 And he arose, and went into his house.
\v 8 And the multitudes seeing it, were afraid, and glorified God that gave such power to men.
\v 9 And when \sc Jesus\sc* passed forth from thence, he saw a man sitting in the custom-house, named Matthew; And he saith to him: Follow me. And he arose up, and followed him. \f + \fr 9:9 \ft The Gospel upon S. Matthew's day. Sept. 21.\f*
\v 10 And it came to pass as he was sitting at meat in the house, behold many Publicans and sinners came, and sat down with \sc Jesus\sc* and his Disciples.
\v 11 And the Pharisees seeing it, said to his disciples: why doth your master eat with Publicans and sinners?
\v 12 But \sc Jesus\sc* hearing it, said: They that are in health, need not a physician, but they that are ill at ease.
\v 13 But go your ways & learn what it is, \add I will mercy, & not sacrifice.\add* For I am not come to call the just, but sinners.
\v 14 Then came to him the Disciples of John, saying: Why do we and the Pharisees fast often, but thy Disciples do not fast?
\v 15 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Can the children of the Bridegroom mourn, as long as the Bridegroom is with them? But the days will come when the Bridegroom shall be taken away from them, and then they shall fast. \f + \fr 9:15 \ft Christ signifieth that the Church shall use fasting days after his Ascension. Epiph. in Comp. fid. Cath. Aug. ep. 80.\f*
\v 16 And nobody putteth a piece of raw cloth to an old garment. For he taketh away the piecing thereof from the garment, and there is made a greater rent.
\v 17 Neither do they put new wine into old bottles. Otherwise the bottles break, and the wine runneth out, and the bottles perish. But new wine they put into new bottles: and both are preserved together.
\v 18 As he was speaking this unto them, behold a certain Governor approached, and adored him, saying: Lord, my daughter is even now dead; but come, lay thy hand upon her, and she shall live. \f + \fr 9:18 \ft The Gospel upon the 23. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 19 And \sc Jesus\sc* rising up followed him, and his Disciples.
\v 20 And behold a woman which was troubled with an issue of blood twelve years, came behind him, and touched the hem of his garment.
\v 21 For she said within herself: If I shall touch only his garment, I shall be safe.
\v 22 But \sc Jesus\sc* turning and seeing her, said: Have a good heart daughter, thy faith hath made thee safe. And the woman became whole from that hour. \f + \fr 9:22 \ft Lo, her devotion to the hem of his garment, was not superstition, but a token of greater faith: so is the devout touching of holy relics.\f*
\v 23 And when \sc Jesus\sc* was come into the house of the Governor, & saw minstrels and the multitude keeping a stir,
\v 24 he said: Depart, for the wench is not dead, but sleepeth. And they laughed him to scorn.
\v 25 And when the multitude was put forth, he entered in, and held her hand. And the maid arose.
\v 26 And this bruit went forth into all that country.
\v 27 And as \sc Jesus\sc* passed forth from thence, there followed him two blind men crying and saying: Have mercy on us, O Son of David.
\v 28 And when he was come to the house, the blind came to him. And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Do you believe, that I can do this unto you? They say to him: Yea Lord.
\v 29 Then he touched their eyes, saying: According to your faith, be it done to you.
\v 30 And their eyes were opened, and \sc Jesus\sc* threatened them, saying: See that no man know it.
\v 31 But they went forth, and bruited him in all that country.
\v 32 And when they were gone forth, behold they brought him a dumb man, possessed with a devil.
\v 33 And after the devil was cast out, the dumb man spake, and the multitudes marveled saying: Never was the like seen in Israel.
\v 34 But the Pharisees said: In the prince of devils he casteth out devils. \f + \fr 9:34 \ft In like manner say the Heretics, calling all miracles done in the Catholic Church, the lying signs of Antichrist.\f*
\v 35 And \sc Jesus\sc* went about all the cities, and towns, teaching in their Synagogues, and preaching the Gospel of the Kingdom, and curing every disease, and every infirmity.
\v 36 And seeing the multitudes, he pitied them; because they were vexed, and lay like sheep that have not a shepherd.
\v 37 Then he saith to his Disciples: The harvest surely is great, but the workmen are few.
\v 38 Pray therefore the Lord of the harvest, that he send forth workmen into his harvest.
\c 10
\p
\v 0 in such times of persecution.
\v 1 \sc And\sc* having called his twelve disciples together, he gave them power over unclean spirits, that they should cast them out, & should cure all manner of disease, & all manner of infirmity.
\v 2 And the names of the twelve Apostles be these: The first, Simon who is called Peter, and Andrew his brother,
\v 3 James of Zebedee, and John his brother, Philip and Barthlemew, Thomas and Matthew the publican, and James of Alphæus, and Thaddæus,
\v 4 Simon Cananæus, & Judas Iscariote, who also betrayed him.
\v 5 These twelve did \sc Jesus\sc* send; commanding them, saying: Into the way of the Gentiles go ye not, and into the cities of the Samaritans enter ye not: \f + \fr 10:5 \ft They have here commission to preach only in Israel: the time being not yet come to call the Gentiles.\f*
\v 6 but go rather to the sheep that are perished of the house of Israel.
\v 7 And going preach, saying: That the Kingdom of Heaven is at hand.
\v 8 Cure the sick, raise the dead, cleanse the lepers, cast out devils: gratis you have received, gratis give ye.
\v 9 Do not possess gold, nor silver, nor money in your purses:
\v 10 not a scrip for the way, neither two coats, neither shoes, neither rod. For the workman is worthy of his meat.
\v 11 And into whatsoever city or town you shall enter, inquire who in it is worthy: and there tarry till you go forth.
\v 12 And when ye enter into the house, salute it, saying: Peace be to this house.
\v 13 And if so be that house be worthy, your peace shall come upon it. But if it be not worthy, your peace shall return to you.
\v 14 And whosoever shall not receive you, nor hear your words; going forth out of the house or the city shake off the dust from your feet.
\v 15 Amen I say to you, it shall be more tolerable for the land of the Sodomites and Gomorrheans in the day of judgement, than for that city.
\v 16 Behold I send you as sheep in the midst of wolves. Be ye therefore wise as serpents, and simple as doves. \f + \fr 10:16 \ft The Gospel upon the Commemoration of S. Paul, Iun. 30.\f* \f + \fr 10:16 \ft Wisdom and simplicity both be necessary in preachers, Bishops and Priests.\f*
\v 17 And take heed of men. For they will deliver you up in Councils, and in their Synagogues they will scourge you.
\v 18 And to presidents and to kings shall you be led for my sake, in testimony to them and the Gentiles.
\v 19 But when they shall deliver you up, take no thought how or what to speak: for it shall be given you in that hour what to speak.
\v 20 For it is not you that speak, but the Spirit of your Father that speaketh in you.
\v 21 The brother also shall deliver up the brother to death, and the father the Son: and the children shall rise up against the parents, and shall work their death,
\v 22 and you shall be odious to all men for my name: but he that shall persevere unto the end, he shall be saved.
\v 23 And when they shall persecute you in this city, flee into another. Amen I say to you, you shall not finish all the cities of Israel, till the Son of man come. \f + \fr 10:23 \ft The Gospel upon S. Athanasius day. Maij 2.\f*
\v 24 The disciple is not above the master, nor the servant above his lord.
\v 25 It sufficeth the disciple that he be as his master, and the servant as his lord. If they have called the goodman of the house Beelzebub, how much more them of his household?
\v 26 Therefore fear ye not them. For nothing is hid, that shall not be revealed: and secret, that shall not be known. \f + \fr 10:26 \ft The Gospel for some Martyrs, not Bishops.\f*
\v 27 That which I speak to you in the dark, speak ye in the light: and that which you hear in the ear, preach ye upon the house tops.
\v 28 And fear ye not them that kill the body, and are not able to kill the soul: but rather fear him that can destroy both soul and body into Hell. \f + \fr 10:28 \ft Agoodly comfort for Christians and Catholics and all good men, in the persecutions of Turk, of Heretics, of all wicked men.\f*
\v 29 Are not two sparrows sold for a farthing: and not one of them shall fall upon the ground without your father?
\v 30 But your very hairs of the head are all numbered.
\v 31 Fear not therefore: better are you than many sparrows.
\v 32 Every one therefore that shall confess me before men, I also will confess him before my Father which is in Heaven.
\v 33 But he that shall deny me before men, I also will deny him before my Father which is in Heaven.
\v 34 Do not ye think that I came to send peace into the earth: I came not to send peace, but the sword. \f + \fr 10:34 \ft The Gospel upon S. Augustine's day our Apostle. Maij 26. And for some Martyrs not Bishops.\f*
\v 35 For I came to separate man against his father, and the daughter against her mother, and the daughter in law against her mother in law.
\v 36 And a man's enemies, they of his own household.
\v 37 He that loveth father or mother more than me, is not worthy of me: and he that loveth son or daughter above me, is not worthy of me.
\v 38 And he that taketh not his cross, and followeth me, is not worthy of me.
\v 39 He that hath found his life, shall lose it: and he that hath lost his life for me, shall find it.
\v 40 He that receiveth you, receiveth me: and he that receiveth me, receiveth him that sent me.
\v 41 He that receiveth a Prophet in the name of a Prophet, shall receive the reward of a Prophet, and he that receiveth a just man in the name of a just man, shall receive the reward of a just man. \f + \fr 10:41 \ft The reward for harbouring & helping any blessed just person suffering for his justice and conscience.\f*
\v 42 And whosoever shall give drink to one of these little ones a cup of cold water, only in the name of a disciple, amen I say to you, he shall not lose his reward.
\c 11
\p
\v 0 God's wisdom in this behalf, 27 and calling to himself all \add such as feel their own burdens.\add*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass: when \sc Jesus\sc* had done commanding his twelve Disciples, he passed from thence, to teach & preach in their cities.
\v 2 And when John had heard in prison the works of Christ; sending two of his Disciples, he said to him: \f + \fr 11:2 \ft The Gospel on the 2. Sunday in Advent.\f*
\v 3 Art thou he that art to come, or look we for another?
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* making answer said to them: Go and report to John what you have heard and seen.
\v 5 The blind see, the lame walk, the lepers are made clean, the deaf hear, the dead rise again, to the poor the Gospel is preached.
\v 6 and blessed is he that shall not be scandalized in me.
\v 7 And when they went their way, \sc Jesus\sc* began to say to the multitudes of John: What went you out into the desert to see? a reed shaken with the wind?
\v 8 But what went you out to see? A man clothed in soft garments? Behold they that are clothed in soft garments, are in kings' houses.
\v 9 But what went you out to see? A Prophet? Yea I tell you and more than a Prophet.
\v 10 For this is he of whom it is written: \add Behold I send mine Angel before thy face, which shall prepare thy way before thee.\add*
\v 11 Amen I say to you, there hath not risen among the born of women a greater than John the Baptist: yet he that is the lesser in the Kingdom of Heaven, is greater than he.
\v 12 And from the days of John the Baptist until now, the Kingdom of Heaven suffereth violence, and the violent bear it away.
\v 13 For all the Prophets and the Law prophesied unto John:
\v 14 and if you will receive it, he is Elias that is for to come.
\v 15 He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.
\v 16 And whereunto shall I esteem this Generation to be like? It is like to children sitting in the market place,
\v 17 which crying to their companions, say: we have piped to you, and you have not danced: we have lamented, and you have not mourned.
\v 18 For John came neither eating nor drinking; and they say: He hath a devil.
\v 19 The Son of man came eating and drinking, and they say: Behold a man that is a glutton and a wine-drinker, a friend of Publicans and sinners. And wisdom is justified of her children.
\v 20 Then began he to upbraid the cities, wherein were done the most of his miracles, for that they had not done penance.
\v 21 Woe be to thee Corozain, woe be to thee Beth-saida: for if in Tyre & Sidon had been wrought the miracles that have been wrought in you, they had done penance in hair-cloth & ashes long ago.
\v 22 But nevertheless, I say to you, it shall be more tolerable for Tyre and Sidon in the day of judgement, than for you.
\v 23 And thou Capharnaum, shalt thou be exalted up to Heaven? thou shalt come down even unto Hell. For if in Sodom had been wrought the miracles that have been wrought in thee, perhaps it had remained unto this day.
\v 24 But notwithstanding I say to you, that it shall be more tolerable for the land of Sodom in the day of judgement, than for thee.
\v 25 At that time \sc Jesus\sc* answered and said: I confess to thee O Father Lord of Heaven and earth, because thou hast hid these things from the wise and prudent, and hast revealed them to little ones. \f + \fr 11:25 \ft The Gospel upon S. Matthias' day Feb. 24. and upon S. Francis' day Octob. 4. and for many Martyrs, and upon S. Paul's day the first Eremite Ian. 15.\f*
\v 26 Yea Father; for so hath it well pleased thee.
\v 27 All things are delivered me of my Father. And no man knoweth the Son but the Father: neither doth any know the Father, but the Son, and to whom it shall please the Son to reveal.
\v 28 Come ye to me all that labour, and are burdened, and I will refresh you.
\v 29 Take up my yoke upon you, and learn of me, because I am meek, and humble of heart: and you shall find rest to your souls.
\v 30 For my yoke is sweet, and my burden light.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 AT that time \sc Jesus\sc* went through the corn on the Sabboth: and his Disciples being hungry, began to pluck the ears, and to eat.
\v 2 And the Pharisees seeing them, said to him: Lo, thy Disciples do that which is not lawful for them to do on the Sabboth-days.
\v 3 But he said to them: Have you not read what David did when he was an hungered, and they that were with him:
\v 4 how he entered into the house of God, and did eat the loaves of proposition, which it was not lawful for him to eat, nor for them that were with him, but for Priests only?
\v 5 Or have ye not read in the Law, that on Sabboth-days the Priests in the temple do break the Sabboth, & are without blame?
\v 6 But I tell you that there is here a greater than the temple.
\v 7 And if you did know what it is, \add I will mercy, and not \add* \add Sacrifice:\add* you would never have condemned the innocents. \f + \fr 12:7 \ft See the annotation chapter. 9, 13.\f*
\v 8 For the Son of man is Lord of the Sabboth also.
\v 9 And when he had passed from thence, he came into their Synagogue.
\v 10 And behold there was a man which had a withered hand, and they asked him saying: Whether is it lawful to cure on the Sabboths? that they might accuse him.
\v 11 But he said to them: What man shall there be of you, that shall have one sheep: and if the same fall into a ditch on the Sabboths, will he not take hold and lift it up?
\v 12 How much better is a man more than a sheep? Therefore it is lawful on the Sabboths to do a good deed.
\v 13 Then he saith to the man: Stretch forth thy hand, and he stretched it forth, and it was restored to health even as the other.
\v 14 And the Pharisees going forth made a consultation against him, how they might destroy him.
\v 15 But \sc Jesus\sc* knowing it, retired from thence: and many followed him, and he cured them all.
\v 16 and he charged them that they should not disclose him.
\v 17 That it might be fulfilled which was spoken by Esay the Prophet, saying:
\v 18 \add Behold my servant whom I have chosen, my beloved in whom my soul hath well liked. I will put my spirit upon him, and judgement to the Gentiles shall he shew.\add*
\v 19 \add He shall not contend, nor cry out, neither shall any man hear in the streets his voice.\add*
\v 20 \add The reed bruised he shall not break, & smoking flax he shall not extinguish: till he cast forth judgement unto victory.\add*
\v 21 \add And in his name the Gentiles shall hope.\add*
\v 22 Then was offered to him one possessed with a devil, blind and dumb: and he cured him, so that he spake and saw.
\v 23 And all the multitudes were amazed, and said: Whether this be the Son of David?
\v 24 But the Pharisees hearing it, said: This fellow casteth not out devils but in Beelzebub the prince of the devils.
\v 25 And \sc Jesus\sc* knowing their cogitations, said to them: Every kingdom divided against itself shall be made desolate: and every city or house divided against itself, shall not stand. \f + \fr 12:25 \ft Therefore the kingdom of heretics cannot possibly stand, because it is always full of division and dissension.\f*
\v 26 And if Satan cast out Satan, he is divided against himself: how then shall his kingdom stand?
\v 27 And if I in Beelzebub cast out devils, your children in whom do they cast out? Therefore they shall be your judges.
\v 28 But if I in the Spirit of God do cast out devils, then is the Kingdom of God come upon you.
\v 29 Or how can a man enter into the house of the strong, and rifle his vessels, unless he first bind the strong? and then he will rifle his house.
\v 30 He that is not with me, is against me: and he that gathereth not with me, scattereth.
\v 31 Therefore I say to you: Every sin and blasphemy shall be forgiven men, but the blasphemy of the Spirit shall not be forgiven.
\v 32 And whosoever shall speak a word against the Son of man, it shall be forgiven him: but he that shall speak against the Holy-Ghost, it shall not be forgiven him neither in this world, nor in the world to come.
\v 33 Either make the tree good, and his fruit good: or make the tree evil, and his fruit evil. For of the fruit the tree is known. \f + \fr 12:33 \ft It is a man's own free will and election, to be a good tree or an ill tree: to bring forth good fruits or bad. S. Augustine upon this place. li. 2. c. 4. de actis cum Felic. Manichæo.\f*
\v 34 You vipers' broods, how can you speak good things, whereas you are evil? For of the aboundance of the heart the mouth speaketh.
\v 35 Agood man out of a good treasure bringeth forth good things: and an evil man out of an evil treasure bringeth forth evil things.
\v 36 But I say unto you, that every idle word that men shall speak, they shall render an account for it in the day of judgement.
\v 37 For of thy words thou shalt be justified, and of thy words thou shalt be condemned.
\v 38 Then answered him certain of the Scribes and Pharisees, saying: Master, we would see a sign from thee. \f + \fr 12:38 \ft The Gospel upon Imber Wednesday, the first week of Lent.\f*
\v 39 Who answered, and said to them: The wicked and adulterous Generation seeketh a sign: and a sign shall not be given it, but the sign of Jonas the Prophet.
\v 40 For as Jonas was in the whale's belly three days and three nights; so shall the Son of man be in the heart of the earth three days and three nights.
\v 41 The men of Ninivee shall rise in the judgement with this Generation, and shall condemn it: because they did penance at the preaching of Jonas. And behold more than Jonas here.
\v 42 The queen of the South shall rise in the judgement with this Generation, and shall condemn it: because she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Salomon, and behold more than Salomon here.
\v 43 And when an unclean spirit shall go out of a man, he walketh through dry places, seeking rest, and findeth not.
\v 44 Then he saith: I will return into my house whence I came out. And coming he findeth it vacant, swept with besoms, and trimmed.
\v 45 Then goeth he, and taketh with him seven other spirits more wicked than himself, and they enter in and dwell there: and the last of that man be made worse than the first. So shall it be also to this wicked Generation.
\v 46 As he was yet speaking to the multitudes, behold his mother and his brethren stood without, seeking to speak to him. \f + \fr 12:46 \ft The Gospel upon the day of the Seven Brethren &c. Iulij 10.\f*
\v 47 And one said unto him: Behold thy mother and thy brethren stand without, seeking thee.
\v 48 But he answering him that told him, said: Who is my mother, and who are my brethren?
\v 49 And stretching forth his hand upon his Disciples, he said: Behold my mother and my brethren.
\v 50 For whosoever shall do the will of my Father, that is in Heaven: he is my brother, and sister, and mother.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 \sc The\sc* same day \sc Jesus\sc* going out of the house, sat by the sea side.
\v 2 And great multitudes were gathered together unto him, in so much that he went up into a boat & sat: and all the multitude stood in the shore;
\v 3 and he spake to them many things in parables, saying: Behold the Sower went forth to sow.
\v 4 And whiles he soweth, some fell by the way side, and the fowls of the air did come and eat it.
\v 5 Other some also fell upon rocky places, where they had not much earth: and they shot up incontinent, because they had not deepness of earth,
\v 6 and after the sun was up, they parched: and because they had not root, they withered.
\v 7 And other fell among thorns: and the thorns grew and choked them.
\v 8 And other some fell upon good ground: and they yielded fruit, the one an hundredfold, the other threescore, and another thirty.
\v 9 He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.
\v 10 And his Disciples came and said to him: Why speakest thou to them in parables?
\v 11 Who answered and said unto them: Because to you it is given to know the mysteries of the Kingdom of Heaven: but to them it is not given.
\v 12 For he that hath, to him shall be given, and he shall abound: but he that hath not, from him shall be taken away that also which he hath.
\v 13 Therefore in parables I speak to them: because seeing they see not, and hearing they hear not, neither do they understand: \f + \fr 13:13 \ft When God's word is preached, they properly have ears to hear, that have hearts to obey: and they hearing do not hear, which hear by sense of their body, and obey not by consent of their hearts. Aug. de dono persev. c. 14.\f*
\v 14 and the Prophecy of Esay is fulfilled in them, which saith: \add With hearing shall you hear; and you shall not understand: and seeing shall you see, and you shall not see.\add*
\v 15 \add For the heart of this people is waxed gross, and with their ears they have heavily heard, and their eyes they have shut: lest at any time they may see with their eyes, and hear with their ears, and understand with their heart and be converted, and I may heal them.\add*
\v 16 But blessed are your eyes because they do see, and your ears because they do hear.
\v 17 For amen I say to you, that many Prophets and just men have desired to see the things that you see, and have not seen them: and to hear the things that you hear, and have not heard them.
\v 18 Hear you therefore the parable of the sower.
\v 19 Every one that heareth the word of the Kingdom and understandeth not, there cometh the wicked one, and catcheth away that which was sown in his heart: this is he that was sown by the way side.
\v 20 And he that was sown upon rocky places: this is he that heareth the word, and incontinent receiveth it with joy,
\v 21 yet hath he not root in himself, but is for a time: and when there falleth tribulation and persecution for the word, he is by and by scandalized.
\v 22 And he that was sown among thorns, this is he that heareth the word, and the carefulness of this world and the deceitfulness of riches choket up the word, and he becometh fruitless.
\v 23 But he that was sown upon good ground: this is he that heareth the word, and understandeth, and bringeth fruit, and yieldeth some an hundred-fold, and another threescore, and another thirty.
\v 24 Another parable he proposed to them, saying: The Kingdom of Heaven is resembled to a man that sowed good seed in his field. \f + \fr 13:24 \ft The Gospel upon the 5. Sunday after the Epiphany.\f*
\v 25 But when men were a sleep, his enemy came and oversowed cockle among the wheat, and went his way.
\v 26 And when the blade was shot up, and had brought forth fruit, then appeared also the cockle.
\v 27 And the servants of the goodman of the house coming said to him: Sir, didst thou not sow good seed in thy field? Whence then hath it cockle?
\v 28 And he said to them: The enemy-man hath done this. And the servants said to him: Wilt thou we go and gather it up?
\v 29 And he said: No lest perhaps gathering up the cockle, you may root up the wheat also together with it.
\v 30 Suffer both to grow until the harvest, and in the time of harvest I will say to the reapers: Gather up first the cockle, and bind it into bundles to burn, but the wheat gather ye into my barn.
\v 31 Another parable he proposed unto them, saying: The Kingdom of Heaven is like to a mustard-seed, which a man took and sowed in his field. \f + \fr 13:31 \ft The Gospel upon the 6 Sunday after the Epiphany.\f*
\v 32 Which is the least surely of all seeds: but when it is grown, it is greater than all herbs, and is made a tree, so that the fowls of the air come, and dwell in the branches thereof.
\v 33 Another parable he spake to them: The Kingdom of Heaven is like to leaven, which a woman took and hid in three measures of meal, until the whole was leavened.
\v 34 All these things \sc Jesus\sc* spake in parables to the multitudes, and without parables he did not speak to them:
\v 35 that it might be fulfilled which was spoken by the Prophet saying: I will open my mouth in parables, \add I will utter things hidden from the foundation of the world.\add*
\v 36 Then having dismissed the multitudes, he came into the house, and his Disciples came unto him, saying: Expound us the parable of the cockle of the field.
\v 37 Who made answer & said to them: He that soweth the good seed, is the Son of man.
\v 38 And the field, is the world. And the good seed: these are the children of the kingdom. And the cockle: are the children of the wicked one.
\v 39 And the enemy that sowed them, is the devil. But the harvest, is the end of the world. And the reapers, are the Angels. \f + \fr 13:39 \ft Not God then, but the Devil is the author of all evil.\f*
\v 40 Even as cockle therefore is gathered up, and burnt with fire: so shall it be in the end of the world.
\v 41 The Son of man shall send his Angels, and they shall gather out of his Kingdom all scandals, and them that work iniquity:
\v 42 and shall cast them into the furnace of fire: There shall be weeping & gnashing of teeth.
\v 43 Then shall the just shine as the sun, in the Kingdom of their Father. He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.
\v 44 The Kingdom of Heaven is like a treasure hidden in a field. Which a man having found, did hide it, and for joy thereof goeth, and selleth all that he hath, and buyeth that field. \f + \fr 13:44 \ft The Gospel upon S. Lucy's day Decemb. 13. And S. Anne Iulij, 26. And for some other Virgins & other holy women.\f*
\v 45 Again the Kingdom of Heaven is like to a merchant man, seeking good pearls.
\v 46 And having found one precious pearl, he went his way, and sold all that he had, and bought it.
\v 47 Again the Kingdom of Heaven is like to a net cast into the sea, and gathering together of all kind of fishes.
\v 48 Which, when it was filled, drawing it forth, and sitting by the shore, they chose out the good into vessels, but the bad they did cast out. \f + \fr 13:48 \ft Here also are signified good and bad in the Church.\f*
\v 49 So shall it be in the consummation of the world. The Angels shall go forth, and shall separate the evil from among the just.
\v 50 And shall cast them into the furnace of fire; there shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
\v 51 Have ye understood all these things? They say to him, Yea.
\v 52 He said unto them: Therefore every Scribe instructed in the Kingdom of Heaven, is like to a man that is an householder, which bringeth forth out of his treasure new things and old.
\v 53 And it came to pass: when \sc Jesus\sc* had ended these parables, he passed from thence.
\v 54 And coming into his own country, he taught them in their Synagogues, so that they marveled, and said: How came this fellow by this wisdom and virtues?
\v 55 Is not this the carpenter's son? Is not his mother called \sc Mary\sc*, and his brethren James, and Joseph, and Simon, and Jude:
\v 56 and his sisters, are they not all with us? Whence therefore hath he all these things?
\v 57 And they were scandalized in him. But \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: There is not a Prophet without honour but in his own country, and in his own house.
\v 58 And he wrought not many miracles there because of their incredulity.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 AT that time Herod the Tetrarch heard the fame of \sc Jesus\sc*:
\v 2 and said to his servants: This is John the Baptist: he is risen from the dead, & therefore virtues work in him.
\v 3 For Herod apprehended John and bound him, & put him into prison because of Herodias, his brother's wife. \f + \fr 14:3 \ft brother Philip's\f*
\v 4 For John said unto him: It is not lawful for thee to have her.
\v 5 And willing to put him to death, he feared the People: because they esteemed him as a Prophet.
\v 6 But on Herod's birth-day, the daughter of Herodias danced before them: and pleased Herod.
\v 7 Whereupon he promised with an oath, to give her whatsoever she would ask of him.
\v 8 But she being instructed before of her mother saith: Give me here in a dish the head of John the Baptist.
\v 9 And the king was stroken sad: yet because of his oath, and for them that sat with him at table, he commanded it to be given. \f + \fr 14:9 \ft Awicked and rash oath, and more wickedly fulfilled: because an unlawful oath bindeth no man.\f*
\v 10 And he sent, and beheaded John in the prison.
\v 11 And his head was brought in a dish: and it was given to the damsel, and she brought it to her mother.
\v 12 And his Disciples came and took the body, and buried it: and came and told \sc Jesus\sc*. \f + \fr 14:12 \ft S. John's disciples at this time had well learned their duty toward Christ.\f*
\v 13 Which when \sc Jesus\sc* had heard, he retired from thence by boat, into a desert place apart, and the multitudes having heard of it, followed him on foot out of the cities.
\v 14 And he coming forth saw a great multitude, and pitied them, and cured their diseased.
\v 15 And when it was evening, his Disciples came unto him, saying: It is a desert place, and the hour is now past: dismiss the multitudes, that going into the towns, they may buy themselves victuals.
\v 16 But \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: They have no need to go: give ye them to eat.
\v 17 They answered him: We have not here, but five loaves, and two fishes.
\v 18 Who said to them: Bring them hither to me.
\v 19 And when he had commanded the multitude to sit down upon the grass, he took the five loaves and the two fishes, and looking up unto Heaven he blessed, and brake, and gave the loaves to his Disciples, and the Disciples to the multitudes.
\v 20 And they did all eat, and had their fill. And they took the leavings, twelve full baskets of the fragments.
\v 21 And the number of them that did eat was, five thousand men, beside women and children.
\v 22 And forthwith \sc Jesus\sc* commanded his Disciples to go up into the boat, and to go before him over the water, till he dismissed the multitudes. \f + \fr 14:22 \ft The Gospel upon the Octave of S. Peter and S. Paul. Iulij 6.\f*
\v 23 And having dismissed the multitude, he ascended into a mountain alone to pray. And when it was evening, he was there alone.
\v 24 But the boat in the midst of the sea was tossed with waves: for the wind was contrary.
\v 25 And in the fourth watch of the night, he came unto them walking upon the sea.
\v 26 And seeing him upon the sea walking, they were troubled saying: That it is a ghost: & for fear they cried out.
\v 27 And immediately \sc Jesus\sc* spake unto them, saying: Have confidence: it is I, fear ye not.
\v 28 And Peter making answer said: Lord if it be thou, bid me come to thee upon the waters.
\v 29 And he said, Come. And Peter descending out of the boat, walked upon the water to come to \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 30 But seeing the wind rough, he was afraid: and when he began to be drowned, he cried out saying: Lord, save me.
\v 31 And incontinent \sc Jesus\sc* stretching forth his hand took hold of him, and said unto him: O thou of little faith, why didst thou doubt? \f + \fr 14:31 \ft Not withstanding the infirmities of them that govern the Church, yet Christ sustaineth them, and holdeth them up, yea and by them, whatsoever they are, he upholdeth and preserveth his Church.\f*
\v 32 And when they were gone up into the boat, the wind ceased.
\v 33 And they that were in the boat, came and adored him, saying: Indeed thou art the Son of God.
\v 34 And having passed the water, they came into the country of Genesar.
\v 35 And when the men of that place understood of him, they sent into all that country, and brought unto him all that were ill at ease:
\v 36 and they besought him that they might touch but the hem of his garment, and whosoever did touch, were made whole. \f + \fr 14:36 \ft See before, chap. 9, 20.\f*
\c 15
\p
\v 1 \sc Then\sc* came to him from Jerusalem Scribes and Pharisees, saying: \f + \fr 15:1 \ft The Gospel upon Wednesday the 3. week in Lent.\f*
\v 2 Why do thy Disciples transgress the tradition of the Ancients? For they wash not their hands when they eat bread.
\v 3 But he answering said to them: Why do you also transgress the commandment of God for your tradition? For God said:
\v 4 \add Honour father and mother.\add* And: \add He that shall curse father or mother, dying let him die.\add*
\v 5 But you say: whosoever shall say to father or mother, the gift whatsoever proceedeth from me, shall profit thee:
\v 6 And shall not honour his father or his mother: & you have made frustrate the commandment of God for your own tradition.
\v 7 Hypocrites, well hath Esay Prophesied of you, saying:
\v 8 \add This People honoureth me with their lips: but their heart is far from me.\add*
\v 9 \add And in vain do they worship me, teaching doctrines and commandments of men.\add*
\v 10 And having called together the multitudes unto him, he said to them: Hear ye and understand.
\v 11 Not that which entereth into the mouth, defileth a man: but that which proceedeth out of the mouth, that defileth a man.
\v 12 Then came his Disciples, and said to him: Dost thou know that the Pharisees, when they heard this word, were scandalized?
\v 13 But he answering said: All planting which my Heavenly Father hath not planted, shall be rooted up.
\v 14 Let them alone: blind they are, guides of the blind. And if the blind be guide to the blind, both fall into the ditch.
\v 15 And Peter answering said to him: Expound us this parable.
\v 16 But he said: Are you also as yet without understanding?
\v 17 Do you not understand, that all that entereth into the mouth, goeth into the belly, and is cast forth into the privy?
\v 18 But the things that proceed out of the mouth, come forth from the heart, and those things defile a man.
\v 19 For from the heart come forth evil cogitations, murders, adulteries, fornications, thefts, false testimonies, blasphemies.
\v 20 These are the things that defile a man. But to eat with unwashen hands, doth not defile a man.
\v 21 And \sc Jesus\sc* went forth from thence and retired into the quarters of Tyre and Sidon. \f + \fr 15:21 \ft The Gospel upon Thursday the first week in Lent.\f*
\v 22 And behold a woman of Chanaan came forth out of those coasts, & crying out, said to him: Have mercy upon me, O Lord the Son of David: my daughter is sore vexed of a devil.
\v 23 Who answered her not a word. And his Disciples came and besought him saying: Dismiss her, because she cryeth out after us.
\v 24 And he answering said: I was not sent but to the sheep that are lost of the house of Israel.
\v 25 But she came and adored him, saying: Lord, help me.
\v 26 Who answering, said: It is not good to take the bread of the Children, and to cast it to the dogs.
\v 27 But she said: Yea Lord; for the whelps also eat of the crumbs that fall from the table of their masters.
\v 28 Then \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to her: O woman, great is thy faith: be it done to thee as thou wilt: And her daughter was made whole from that hour. \f + \fr 15:28 \ft It were a strange case that Christ should commend in this woman a sole faith without good works, that is to say, a dead faith such as could not work by love, and which S. James doubted not to call the faith not of Christians but of Devils. Aug. de Fid. & Op. c. 16.\f*
\v 29 And when \sc Jesus\sc* was passed from thence, he came beside the sea of Galilee: & ascending into the mountain, sat there.
\v 30 And there came to him great multitudes, having with them dumb persons, blind, lame, feeble, and many others: and they cast them down at his feet, and he cured them:
\v 31 So that the multitudes marveled seeing the dumb speak, the lame walk, the blind see: and they magnified the God of Israel.
\v 32 And \sc Jesus\sc* called together his Disciples, and said: I pity the multitude because three days now they continue with me, & have not what to eat: and dismiss them fasting I will not, lest they faint in the way.
\v 33 And the Disciples say unto him: whence then may we get so many loaves in the desert as to fill so great a multitude?
\v 34 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: How many loaves have you? But they said: Seven, & a few little fishes.
\v 35 And he commanded the multitude to sit down upon the ground.
\v 36 And taking the Seven loaves & the fishes, and giving thanks, he brake, & gave it to his Disciples, and the Disciples gave to the people. \f + \fr 15:36 \ft Here we see again that the people must not be their own carvers, nor receive the Sacraments or other spiritual sustenance immediately of Christ, or at their own hand, but of their spiritual governers.\f*
\v 37 And they did all eat, and had their fill. And that which was left of the fragments they took up, seven baskets full.
\v 38 And there were that did eat, four thousand men, beside children & women.
\v 39 And having dismissed the multitude, he went up into a boat, and came into the coasts of Magedan.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there came to him the Pharisees and Sadducees tempting: and they demanded him to shew them a sign from Heaven.
\v 2 But he answered & said to them: When it is evening, you say: It will be fair-weather, for the element is red.
\v 3 And in the morning: This day there will be a tempest, for the element doth glow and lower. The face therefore of the element you have skill to discern: & the signs of times can you not?
\v 4 The naughty and adulterous Generation seeketh for a sign: and there shall not a sign be given it, but the sign of Jonas the Prophet. And he left them and went away.
\v 5 And when his Disciples were come over the water, they forgot to take bread.
\v 6 Who said to them: Look well and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees & Sadducees.
\v 7 But they thought within themselves saying: Because we took not bread.
\v 8 And \sc Jesus\sc* knowing it, said: Why do you think within yourselves, O ye of little faith, for that you have not bread?
\v 9 Do you not yet understand, neither do you remember the five loaves among five thousand men, and how many baskets you took up?
\v 10 neither the seven loaves, among four thousand men, and how many maunds you took up?
\v 11 Why do you not understand that I said not of bread to you: Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees, & Sadducees?
\v 12 Then they understood that he said not they should beware of the leaven of bread, but of the doctrine of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
\v 13 And \sc Jesus\sc* came into the quarters of Cæsarea Philippi: and he asked his Disciples, saying: whom say men that the Son of man is? \f + \fr 16:13 \ft The Gospel upon SS. Peter and Paul's day Iun. 29. And in Cathedra Petri Romæ, Ian. 18. & Antiochiæ Febr. 22. And Petri ad vincula Aug. 1. And on the day of the creation and coronation of the Pope, and on the Anniversary thereof. And upon S. Leo his day April 11.\f*
\v 14 But they said: Some John the Baptist, & othersome Elias, and others Jeremie, or one of the Prophets.
\v 15 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: But whom do you say that I am?
\v 16 Simon Peter answered & said: Thou art Christ the Son of the living God.
\v 17 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said to him: Blessed art thou Simon Bar-Jona: because flesh & blood hath not revealed it to thee, but my Father which is in Heaven.
\v 18 And I say to thee: \add That thou art\add* Peter; \add and upon this\add* Rock \add will I build my Church, and the gates of Hell shall not prevail\add* against it. \f + \fr 16:18 \ft That is, a Rock.\f*
\v 19 \add And I will give to thee the keys of the Kingdom of Heaven. And whatsoever thou shalt bind upon earth, it shall be bound also in the Heavens: and whatsoever thou shalt loose in earth, it shall be loosed also in the Heavens.\add*
\v 20 Then he commanded his Disciples, that they should tell nobody that he was \sc Jesus Christ\sc*.
\v 21 From that time \sc Jesus\sc* began to shew his Disciples, that he must go to Jerusalem, & suffer many things of the Ancients & Scribes and Chief-Priests, and be killed, and the third day rise again.
\v 22 And Peter taking him unto him, began to rebuke him, saying: Lord, be it far from thee, this shall not be unto thee.
\v 23 Who turning said to Peter: Go after me Satan, thou art a scandal unto me: because thou savourest not the things that are of God, but the things that are of men. \f + \fr 16:23 \ft This word in Hebrew signifieth an adversary, as 3. Reg.\f*
\v 24 Then \sc Jesus\sc* said to his Disciples: If any man will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross, and follow me. \f + \fr 16:24 \ft THE Gospel for a Martyr that is a bishop; And upon S. Laurence Eve.\f*
\v 25 For he that will save his life, shall lose it, and he that shall lose his life for me, shall find it.
\v 26 For what doth it profit a man, if he gain the whole world, and sustain the damage of his soul? Or what permutation shall a man give for his soul?
\v 27 For the Son of man shall come in the glory of his Father with his Angels: and then will he render to every man according to his works.
\v 28 Amen I say to you, there be some of them that stand here, that shall not taste death, till they see the Son of man coming in his Kingdom. \f + \fr 16:28 \ft Cyr. l. 8. c. 12. Com. in Io.\f*
\c 17
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* after six days \sc Jesus\sc* taketh unto him Peter, and James, & John his brother, & bringeth them into a high mountain apart: \f + \fr 17:1 \ft The Transfiguration of our Lord, celebrated in the Church the 6. of Aug. The Gospel of the said feast, & of the 2. Sunday in Lent: and on Imber Saturday before.\f*
\v 2 And he was transfigured before them. And his face did shine as the sun: & his garments became white as snow.
\v 3 And behold there appeared to them Moyses and Elias talking with him.
\v 4 And Peter answering, said to \sc Jesus\sc*: Lord, it is good for us to be here: if thou wilt, let us make here three tabernacles, one for thee, and one for Moyses, and one for Elias.
\v 5 And as he was yet speaking, behold a bright cloud overshadowed them. And lo a voice out of the cloud, saying: This is my wellbeloved Son, in whom I am well pleased: hear ye him.
\v 6 And the Disciples hearing it, fell upon their face, and were sore afraid.
\v 7 And \sc Jesus\sc* came and touched them: and he said to them: Arise, and fear not.
\v 8 And they lifting up their eyes, saw nobody, but only \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 9 And as they descended from the mount, \sc Jesus\sc* commanded them, saying: Tell the vision to nobody, till the Son of man be risen from the dead.
\v 10 And his Disciples asked him, saying: what say the Scribes then, that Elias must come first?
\v 11 But he answering, said to them: Elias indeed shall come, and restore all things.
\v 12 And I say to you, that Elias is already come, and they did not know him, but wrought on him whatsoever they would. So also the Son of man shall suffer of them.
\v 13 Then the Disciples understood, that of John the Baptist he had spoken to them.
\v 14 And when he was come unto the multitude, there came to him a man falling down upon his knees before him, saying: Lord have mercy upon my Son, for he is lunatic, and sore vexed: for he falleth often into the fire, and often into the water.
\v 15 And I offered him to thy Disciples, and they could not cure him.
\v 16 \sc Jesus\sc* answered and said: O faithless and perverse generation, how long shall I be with you? How long shall I suffer you? Bring him hither to me.
\v 17 And \sc Jesus\sc* rebuked him, and the devil went out of him, and the lad was cured from that hour.
\v 18 Then came the Disciples to \sc Jesus\sc* secretly, and said: Why could we not cast him out?
\v 19 \sc Jesus\sc* said to them, because of your incredulity: For, Amen I say to you, if you have faith as a mustard seed, you shall say to this mountain, Remove from thence thither, and it shall remove; and nothing shall be impossible to you.
\v 20 But this kind is not cast out but by prayer and fasting.
\v 21 And when they conversed in Galilee, \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: The Son of man is to be betrayed into the hands of men:
\v 22 and they shall kill him, and the third day he shall rise again. And they were stroken sad exceedingly.
\v 23 And when they were come to Capharnaum, there came they that received the didrachmes, unto Peter, and said to him: Your master doth he not pay the didrachmes? \f + \fr 17:23 \ft These didrachmes were pieces of money which they payed for tribute.\f*
\v 24 He saith, Yes. And when he was entered into the house, \sc Jesus\sc* prevented him, saying: What is thy opinion Simon? The kings of the earth, of whom receive they tribute or cense? Of their children, or of strangers?
\v 25 And he said: Of strangers. \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Then the children are free.
\v 26 But that we may not scandalize them, go thy ways to the sea, and cast a hook: and that fish which shall first come up, take: and when thou hast opened his mouth, thou shalt find a stater: take that, and give it them for me and thee. \f + \fr 17:26 \ft This stater was a double didrachme, and therefore was payed for two.\f*
\c 18
\p
\v 1 AT that hour the Disciples came to \sc Jesus\sc*, saying: Who, thinkest thou, is the greater in the Kingdom of Heaven? \f + \fr 18:1 \ft The Gospel on Michaelmas day Septemb. 29. And upon his Apparition. Maij 8.\f*
\v 2 And \sc Jesus\sc* calling unto him a little child, set him in the midst of them,
\v 3 and said: Amen I say to you, unless you be converted, and become as little children, you shall not enter into the Kingdom of Heaven.
\v 4 Whosoever therefore shall humble himself as this little child, he is the greater in the Kingdom of Heaven. \f + \fr 18:4 \ft Humility, innocency, simplicity, commended to us in the state and person of a child.\f*
\v 5 And he that shall receive one such little child in my name, receiveth me.
\v 6 And he that shall scandalize one of these little ones that believe in me, it is expedient for him that a millstone be hanged about his neck, and that he be drowned in the depth of the sea.
\v 7 Woe be to the world for scandals. For it is necessary that scandals do come: but nevertheless woe to that man by whom the scandal cometh.
\v 8 And if thy hand, or thy foot scandalize thee, cut it off, and cast it from thee. It is good for thee to go into life maimed or lame, rather than having two hands or two feet, to be cast into everlasting fire.
\v 9 And if thine eye scandalize thee, pluck him out, and cast him from thee: It is good for thee having one eye to enter into life, rather than having two eyes to be cast into the Hell of fire.
\v 10 See that you despise not one of these little ones: for I say to you, that their Angels in Heaven always do see the face of my Father which is in Heaven.
\v 11 For the Son of man is come to save that which was perished.
\v 12 How think you? If a man have an hundred sheep, and one of them shall go astray; doth he not leave ninety nine in the mountains, and goeth to seek that which is strayed?
\v 13 And if it chance that he find it: Amen I say to you, that he rejoiceth more for that, than for the ninety nine that went not astray.
\v 14 Even so it is not the will of your Father, which is in Heaven, that one perish of these little ones.
\v 15 But if thy brother shall offend against thee, go, and rebuke him between thee and him alone. If he shall hear thee, thou shalt gain thy brother. \f + \fr 18:15 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday the 3 week in Lent.\f*
\v 16 And if he will not hear thee, join with thee besides, one or two: that in the mouth of two or three witnesses every word may stand.
\v 17 And if he will not hear them, tell the Church. \add And if he will not hear the Church, let him be to thee as the Heathen and the Publican.\add* \f + \fr 18:17 \ft That is (as S. Chrysostom here expoundeth it) tell the Prelates and chief Pastors of the Church: for they have jurisdiction to bind and loose such offenders, by the words following v. 18.\f*
\v 18 Amen I say to you, whatsoever you shall bind upon earth, shall be bound also in Heaven: and whatsoever you shall loose upon earth, shall be loosed also in Heaven.
\v 19 Again I say to you, that if two of you shall consent upon earth, concerning every thing whatsoever they shall ask, it shall be done to them of my Father which is in Heaven. \f + \fr 18:19 \ft All joining together in the unity of Christ's Church in Councels and Synods, or public prayers, is of more force than of any particular man.\f*
\v 20 For where there be two or three gathered in my name, there am I in the midst of them.
\v 21 Then came Peter unto him and said: Lord, how often shall my brother offend against me, & I forgive him? Until seven times?
\v 22 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: I say not to thee until seven times but until seventy times seven times.
\v 23 Therefore is the Kingdom of Heaven likened to a man being a king, that would make an account with his servants. \f + \fr 18:23 \ft The Gospel upon the 21. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 24 And when he began to make the account, there was one presented unto him that owed him ten thousand talents.
\v 25 And having not whence to repay it, his Lord commanded that he should be sold, and his wife and children, and all that he had, and it to be repayed.
\v 26 But that servant falling down, besought him, saying: Have patience toward me, and I will repay thee all,
\v 27 And the Lord of that servant moved with pity, dismissed him, and the debt he forgave him.
\v 28 And when that servant was gone forth, he found one of his fellow-servants that did owe him an hundred pence: and laying hands upon him throttled him, saying: Repay that thou owest.
\v 29 And his fellow-servant falling down, besought him, saying: Have patience toward me, and I will repay thee all.
\v 30 And he would not: but went his way, and cast him into prison, till he repayed the debt.
\v 31 And his fellow-servants seeing what was done, were very sorry, and they came, and told their Lord all that was done.
\v 32 Then his Lord called him; and he said unto him: Thou ungracious servant, I forgave thee all the debt, because thou besoughtest me:
\v 33 oughtest not thou therefore also to have mercy upon thy fellow-servant, even as I had mercy upon thee?
\v 34 And his Lord being angry delivered him to the tormenters, until he repayed all the debt.
\v 35 So also shall my Heavenly Father do to you, if you forgive not every one his brother from your hearts.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass, when \sc Jesus\sc* had ended these words, he departed from Galilee, and came into the coasts of Jury beyond Jordan,
\v 2 and great multitudes followed him; and he cured them there.
\v 3 And there came to him the Pharisees tempting him, and saying: Is it lawful for a man to dismiss his wife for every cause? \f + \fr 19:3 \ft The Gospel for Marriage, and upon S. Agatha's day. Feb. 5.\f*
\v 4 Who answering, said to them: Have ye not read, that he which did make from the beginning, \add made them male & female?\add* And he said: \f + \fr 19:4 \ft make man\f*
\v 5 \add For this cause, man shall leave father & mother, & shall cleave to his wife, and they two shall be in one flesh.\add*
\v 6 Therefore now they are not two, but one flesh. That therefore which God hath joined together, let not man separate.
\v 7 They say to him: Why then did Moyses command to give a bill of divorce, and to dismiss her?
\v 8 He saith to them: Because Moyses for the hardness of your heart permitted you to dismiss your wives: but from the beginning it was not so.
\v 9 And I say to you, that whosoever shall dismiss his wife, but for fornication, and shall marry another, doth commit adultery: and he that shall marry her that is dismissed, committeth adultery.
\v 10 His Disciples say unto him: If the case of a man with his wife be so, it is not expedient to marry.
\v 11 Who said to them: Not all take this word, but they to whom it is given. \f + \fr 19:11 \ft χωροῦσι. capiunt.\f*
\v 12 For there are Eunuchs which were born so from their mother's womb: and there are Eunuchs, which were made by men: and there are Eunuchs, which have gelded themselves for the Kingdom of Heaven. He that can take, let him take.
\v 13 Then were little children presented to him, that he should impose hands upon them & pray. And the Disciples rebuked them.
\v 14 But \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Suffer the little children, and stay them not from coming unto me: for the Kingdom of Heaven is for such.
\v 15 And when he had imposed hands upon them, he departed from thence.
\v 16 And behold one came and said to him: Good Master, what good shall I do that I may have life everlasting?
\v 17 Who said to him: What asketh thou me of good? One is good, God. But if thou wilt enter into life, keep the commandments. \f + \fr 19:17 \ft Isee not (saith S. Augustine) why Christ should say, if thou wilt have life everlasting, keep the commandments: if without observing of them, by only faith one might be saved. Aug. de Fid. & op. c. 15.\f*
\v 18 He saith to him, which? And \sc Jesus\sc* said: \add Thou shalt not murder, Thou shalt not commit adultery, Thou shalt not steal, Thou shalt not bear false witness.\add*
\v 19 \add Honour thy father & thy mother, \add* \add Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself.\add*
\v 20 The young man saith to him: All these have I kept from my youth; what is yet wanting unto me?
\v 21 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: If thou wilt be perfect, go, sell the things that thou hast, & give to the poor, and thou shalt have treasure in Heaven: and come, follow me.
\v 22 And when the young man had heard this word, he went away sad: for he had many possessions.
\v 23 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to his Disciples: Amen I say to you, that a rich man shall hardly enter into the Kingdom of Heaven.
\v 24 And again I say to you, it is easier for a camel to pass through the eye of a needle, than for a rich man to enter into the Kingdom of Heaven. \f + \fr 19:24 \ft S. Mark expoundeth it thus, rich men trusting in their riches. ca. 10, 24.\f*
\v 25 And when they had heard this, the Disciples marveled very much, saying: Who then can be saved?
\v 26 And \sc Jesus\sc* beholding, said to them: With men this is impossible: but with God all things are possible.
\v 27 Then Peter answering, said to him: Behold we have left all things, & have followed thee: what therefore shall we have? \f + \fr 19:27 \ft The Gospel upon the Conversion of S. Paul. Ian. 25. Also within the Octave, and in a votive Mass of SS. Peter & Paul, and for holy abbots.\f*
\v 28 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Amen I say to you, that you which have followed me, in the regeneration, when the Son of man shall sit in the seat of his majesty, you also shall sit upon twelve seats, judging the twelve Tribes of Israel.
\v 29 And every one that hath left house, or brethren, or sisters, or father, or mother, or wife, or children, or lands for my name's sake: shall receive an hundred-fold, & shall possess life everlasting. \f + \fr 19:29 \ft Hereof is gathered that the Apostles among other things left their wives also to follow Christ. Hiero. li. 1. adv. Iovin.\f*
\v 30 And many shall be first, that are last; and last, that are first.
\c 20
\p
\v 0 Jericho, he giveth sight unto two blind.
\v 1 \sc The\sc* Kingdom of Heaven is like to a man that is an householder which went forth early in the morning to hire workmen into his vineyard. \f + \fr 20:1 \ft The Gospel upon the Sunday of Septuagesima.\f*
\v 2 And having made covenant with the workmen for a penny a day, he sent them into his vineyard.
\v 3 And going forth about the third hour, he saw other standing in the market place idle,
\v 4 and he said to them: Go you also into the vineyard, and that which shall be just, I will give you.
\v 5 And they went their way. And again he went forth about the sixth & the ninth hour: and did likewise.
\v 6 But about the eleventh hour he went forth and found other standing, & he saith to them: What stand you here all the day idle?
\v 7 They say to him: Because no man hath hired us. He saith to them: Go you also into the vineyard.
\v 8 And when evening was come, the Lord of the vineyard saith to his bailiff, Call the workmen, and pay them their hire, beginning from the last even to the first.
\v 9 Therefore when they were come that came about the eleventh hour, they received every one a penny.
\v 10 But when the first also came, they thought that they should receive more: and they also received every one a penny.
\v 11 And receiving it they murmured against the good-man of the house. \f + \fr 20:11 \ft The Jews are noted for envying the vocation of the Gentiles, and their reward equal with themselves.\f*
\v 12 Saying: These last have continued one hour, and thou hast made them equal to us that have borne the burden of the day & the heats.
\v 13 But he answering said to one of them, Friend, I do thee no wrong: didst thou not covenant with me for a penny?
\v 14 Take that is thine, and go: I will also give to this last even as to thee also.
\v 15 Or, is it not lawful for me to do that I will? Is thine eye naught, because I am good?
\v 16 So shall the last be first, and the first, last. For many be called, but few elect.
\v 17 And \sc Jesus\sc* going up to Jerusalem, took the twelve Disciples secretly, and said to them: \f + \fr 20:17 \ft The Gospel upon Wednesday the 2. week in Lent. And in a votive Mass of the holy Cross.\f*
\v 18 Behold we go up to Jerusalem, and the Son of man shall be delivered to the chief Priests and to the Scribes, and they shall condemn him to death,
\v 19 and shall deliver him to the Gentiles to be mocked, and scourged, and crucified, and the third day he shall rise again.
\v 20 Then came to him the mother of the sons of Zebedee with her sons, adoring and desiring something of him. \f + \fr 20:20 \ft The Gospel upon S. Jame's day. Iul. 25. And S. John's ante portam Latinam Maij 6.\f*
\v 21 Who said to her: What wilt thou? She saith to him: Say that these my two sons may sit, one at thy right hand, & one at thy left hand in thy Kingdom.
\v 22 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said: You know not what you desire. Can you drink of the cup that I shall drink of? They say to him: We can.
\v 23 He saith to them: My cup indeed you shall drink of: but to sit at my right hand and left, is not mine to give to you: but to whom it is prepared of my Father.
\v 24 And the ten hearing it, were displeased at the two brethren.
\v 25 And \sc Jesus\sc* calleth them unto him, and said: You know that the princes of the Gentiles overrule them: and they that are the greater, exercise power against them. \f + \fr 20:25 \ft Superiority is not here forbidden among Christians, neither Ecclesiastical nor temporal; but heathenish tyranny is forbidden, and humility commended.\f*
\v 26 It shall not be so among you, but whosoever will be the greater among you, let him be your minister:
\v 27 And he that will be first among you, shall be your servant.
\v 28 Even as the Son of man is not come to be ministered unto, but to minister, and to give his life a redemption for many.
\v 29 And when they went out from Jericho, a great multitude followed him.
\v 30 And behold two blind men sitting by the way side, heard that \sc Jesus\sc* passed by, and they cried out saying: Lord, have mercy upon us, Son of David.
\v 31 And the multitude rebuked them that they should hold their peace. But they cried out the more, saying: Lord, have mercy upon us, Son of David.
\v 32 And \sc Jesus\sc* stood, and called them, and said: What will ye that I do to you?
\v 33 They say to him: Lord, that our eyes may be opened.
\v 34 And \sc Jesus\sc* having compassion on them, touched their eyes. And immediately they saw, and followed him. \f + \fr 20:34 \ft Our Saviour who always could, and often did cure the diseased, by his only will, or word, here gave sight to these blind men, by touching their eyes with his holy hand.\f*
\c 21
\p
\v 0 consequently their irreparable damnation that shall \add ensue thereof.\add* \f + \fr 21:0 \ft THE FIFTH part of this Gospel. Of the Holy Week of his Passion in Hierusalem.\f*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when they drew nigh to Jerusalem, and were come to Beth-phagee unto Mount-olivet, then \sc Jesus\sc* sent two Disciples, \f + \fr 21:1 \ft The Gospel on Palm Sunday before the benediction of the Palms.\f*
\v 2 saying to them: Go ye into the town that is against you, and immediately you shall find an ass tied and a colt with her: loose them & bring them to me: \f + \fr 21:2 \ft PALM SUNDAY.\f*
\v 3 And if any man shall say ought unto you, say ye, that our Lord hath need of them: and forthwith he will let them go.
\v 4 And this was done that it might be fulfilled which was spoken by the Prophet, saying:
\v 5 \add Say ye to the daughter of Sion: Behold thy King cometh to thee, meek, & sitting upon an ass and a colt the foal of her that is used to the yoke.\add*
\v 6 And the Disciples going, did as \sc Jesus\sc* commanded them.
\v 7 And they brought the ass and the colt: and laid their garments upon them, and made him to sit thereon.
\v 8 And a very great multitude spread their garments in the way: and others did cut boughs from the trees, and strawed them in the way:
\v 9 and the multitudes that went before and that followed, cried, saying: \add Hosanna to the Son of David: Blessed is he that cometh in the name of our Lord. Hosanna in the highest.\add*
\v 10 And when he was entered Jerusalem, the whole city was moved, saying: Who is this? \f + \fr 21:10 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday in the first week in Lent.\f*
\v 11 And the People said: This is \sc Jesus\sc* the Prophet, of Nazareth in Galilee.
\v 12 And \sc Jesus\sc* entered into the temple of God, and cast out all that sold and bought in the temple, and the tables of the bankers, & the chairs of them that sold pigeons he overthrew: \f + \fr 21:12 \ft How much the abuse of Churches by merchandising, walking, or other profane occupying of them, displeaseth God, here we may see.\f*
\v 13 and he saith to them: It is written, \add My house shall be called the house of prayer: but you have made it a den of thieves.\add*
\v 14 And there came to him the blind, and the lame in the temple; and he healed them.
\v 15 And the chief Priests & Scribes seeing the marvelous things that he did, and the children crying in the temple, & saying, \add Hosanna to the Son of David;\add* they had indignation,
\v 16 and said to him: Hearest thou what these say? And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Very well. Have you never read: \add That out of the mouth of infants and sucklings thou hast perfited praise?\add*
\v 17 And leaving them, he went forth out of the city into Bethania, and remained there.
\v 18 And in the morning returning into the city, he was an hungered. \f + \fr 21:18 \ft MONDAY.\f*
\v 19 And seeing a certain figtree by the way side, he came to it, and found nothing on it but leaves only, and he saith to it: Never grow there fruit of thee for ever. And incontinent the figtree was withered. \f + \fr 21:19 \ft The Jews having the words of the law, and not the deeds, were the fig tree full of leaves, and void of fruit. Aug. de verb. Do. Serm. 44.\f*
\v 20 And the Disciples seeing it, marveled saying: How is it withered incontinent?
\v 21 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to them: Amen I say to you, if you shall have faith, and stagger not, not only that of the figtree shall you do, but and if you shall say to this mountain, Take up and throw thyself into the sea, it shall be done. \f + \fr 21:21 \ft b TUESDAY.\f*
\v 22 And all things whatsoever you shall ask in prayer believing, you shall receive.
\v 23 And when he was come into the temple, there came to him as he was teaching, the chief Priests and ancients of the people, saying: In what power doest thou these things? and who hath given thee this power?
\v 24 \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to them: I also will ask you one word, which if you shall tell me, I also will tell you in what power I do these things.
\v 25 The Baptism of John whence was it? from Heaven, or from men? But they thought within themselves, saying:
\v 26 If we shall say from Heaven, he will say to us, why then did you not believe him? But if we shall say from men, we fear the multitude, for all hold John as a Prophet.
\v 27 And answering to \sc Jesus\sc* they said: We know not. He also said to them: Neither do I tell you in what power I do these things.
\v 28 But what is your opinion? A certain man had two sons, and coming to the first, he said: Son, go work today in my vineyard.
\v 29 And he answering, said: I will not. But afterward moved with repentance he went.
\v 30 And coming to the other, he said likewise. And he answering, said: I go Lord, and he went not:
\v 31 Which of the two did the father's will? They say to him: The first. \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Amen I say to you, that the Publicans and whores go before you into the Kingdom of God.
\v 32 For John came to you in the way of justice, and you did not believe him. But the Publicans and whores did believe him: but you seeing it, neither have ye had repentance afterward, to believe him.
\v 33 Another parable hear ye: A man there was an householder who planted a vineyard, and made a hedge round about it, and digged in it a press, and builded a tower, and let it out to husbandmen: and went forth into a strange country. \f + \fr 21:33 \ft The Gospel upon Friday the 2. week in Lent.\f*
\v 34 And when the time of fruits drew nigh, he sent his servants to the husbandmen, to receive the fruits thereof.
\v 35 And the husbandmen apprehending his servants, one they beat, another they killed, and another they stoned.
\v 36 Again he sent other servants more than the former: and they did to them likewise.
\v 37 And last of all he sent to them his son, saying: They will reverence my son.
\v 38 But the husbandmen seeing the son, said within themselves: This is the heir, come, let us kill him, and we shall have his inheritance.
\v 39 And apprehending him they cast him forth out of the vineyard, & killed him.
\v 40 When therefore the Lord of the vineyard shall come, what will he do to those husbandmen?
\v 41 They say to him: The naughty men he will bring to naught: and his vineyard he will let out to other husbandmen, that shall render him the fruit in their seasons.
\v 42 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Have you never read in the Scriptures: \add The stone which the builders rejected, the same is made into the head of the corner? By our Lord was this done, and it is marvelous in our eyes.\add*
\v 43 Therefore I say to you, that the Kingdom of God shall be taken away from you, and shall be given to a Nation yielding the fruits thereof.
\v 44 And he that falleth upon this stone, shall be broken: and on whom it falleth, it shall all to bruise him.
\v 45 And when the chief Priests and Pharisees had heard his parables, they knew that he spake of them.
\v 46 And seeking to lay hands upon him, they feared the multitudes: because they held him as a Prophet.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 \sc And Jesus\sc* answering, spake again in parables to them, saying: \f + \fr 22:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 19. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 2 The Kingdom of Heaven is likened to a man being a king, which made a marriage to his son.
\v 3 And he sent his servants to call them that were invited to the marriage: and they would not come.
\v 4 Again he sent other servants, saying: Tell them that were invited, Behold I have prepared my dinner; my beeves & fatlings are killed, and all things are ready: come ye to the marriage.
\v 5 But they neglected and went their ways, one to his farm, and another to his merchandise:
\v 6 and the rest laid hands upon his servants, and spitefully entreating them, murdered them.
\v 7 But when the king had heard of it, he was wroth, and sending his hosts, destroyed those murderers, and burnt their city.
\v 8 Then he saith to his servants: The marriage indeed is ready: but they that were invited, were not worthy.
\v 9 Go ye therefore into the high ways; and whosoever you shall find, call to the marriage.
\v 10 And his servants going forth into the ways, gathered together all that they found, bad and good: and the marriage was filled with guests. \f + \fr 22:10 \ft Not only good men be within the Church, but also evil men; against the Heretics of these days.\f*
\v 11 And the king went in to see the guests: and he saw there a man not attired in a wedding garment.
\v 12 And he saith to him: Friend, how camest thou in hither not having a wedding garment? But he was dumb.
\v 13 Then the king said to the waiters: Bind his hands and feet, and cast him into the utter darkness: there shall be weeping & gnashing of teeth.
\v 14 For many be called, but few elect.
\v 15 Then the Pharisees departing, consulted among themselves for to entrap him in his talk. \f + \fr 22:15 \ft The Gospel upon the 22. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 16 And they send to him their disciples with the Herodians, saying: Master, we know that thou art a true speaker, and teachest the way of God in truth, neither carest thou for any man. For thou dost not respect the person of men:
\v 17 Tell us therefore what is thy opinion, is it lawful to give tribute to Cæsar, or not?
\v 18 But \sc Jesus\sc* knowing their naughtiness, said: What do you tempt me Hypocrites?
\v 19 Shew me the tribute coin. And they offered him a penny.
\v 20 And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Whose is this image and superscription?
\v 21 They say to him, Cæsar's. Then he saith to them: Render therefore the things that are Cæsar's, to Cæsar: and the things that are God's, to God.
\v 22 And hearing it they marveled, and leaving him went their ways.
\v 23 That day there came to him the Sadducees, that say there is no resurrection, and asked him,
\v 24 saying: Master, Moyses said, \add If a man die not having a child, that his brother marry his wife, and raise up seed to his brother.\add*
\v 25 And there were with us seven brethren: and the first having married a wife, died; and not having issue, left his wife to his brother.
\v 26 In like manner the second and the third even to the seventh.
\v 27 And last of all the woman died also.
\v 28 In the Resurrection therefore whose wife of the seven shall she be? For they all had her.
\v 29 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said to them: You do err, not knowing the Scriptures, nor the power of God.
\v 30 For in the resurrection neither shall they marry nor be married: but are as the Angels of God in Heaven.
\v 31 And concerning the resurrection of the dead, have you not read that which was spoken of God saying to you.
\v 32 \add I am the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob?\add* He is not God of the dead, but of the living.
\v 33 And the multitudes hearing it, marveled at his doctrine.
\v 34 But the Pharisees hearing that he had put the Sadducees to silence, came together: \f + \fr 22:34 \ft The Gospel upon the 17. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 35 and one of them a doctor of law asked of him, tempting him:
\v 36 Master, which is the great commandment in the law?
\v 37 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: \add Thou shalt love the Lord thy God from thy whole heart, and with thy whole soul, and with thy whole mind.\add*
\v 38 This is the greatest & the first commandment.
\v 39 And the second is like to this: \add Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself.\add*
\v 40 On these two commandments dependeth the whole Law and the Prophets.
\v 41 And the Pharisees being assembled, \sc Jesus\sc* asked them
\v 42 saying: What is your opinion of Christ? whose son is he? They say to him, David's.
\v 43 He saith to them: How then doth David in spirit call him Lord, saying:
\v 44 \add The Lord said to my Lord, sit on my right hand, until I put thine enemies the foot-stool of thy feet?\add*
\v 45 If David therefore call him Lord, how is he his son?
\v 46 And no man could answer him a word: neither durst any man from that day ask him any more.
\c 23
\p
\v 1 \sc Then Jesus\sc* spake to the multitudes and to his Disciples, \f + \fr 23:1 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday the second week in Lent.\f*
\v 2 saying: Upon the chair of Moyses have sitten the Scribes and the Pharisees.
\v 3 All things therefore whatsoever they shall say to you, observe ye and do ye: but according to their works do ye not, for they say and do not.
\v 4 For they bind heavy burdens & importable: & put them upon men's shoulders: but with a finger of their own they will not move them.
\v 5 But they do all their works for to be seen of men. For they make broad their phylacteries, and enlarge their fringes. \f + \fr 23:5 \ft These phylacteries were pieces of parchment, wherein they wrote the ten commandments, and folded it, and carried it on their forehead before their eyes, imagining grossly and superstitiously, that so they fulfilled that which is said Deu. 6, They shall be immovable before thine eyes. Hiero. in 23. Mat.\f*
\v 6 And they love the first places at suppers, and the first chairs in the Synagogues,
\v 7 and salutations in the market-place, and to be called of men, Rabbi.
\v 8 But be not you called Rabbi. For one is your Master, and all you are brethren.
\v 9 And call none Father to yourself upon earth: for one is your Father, he that is in Heaven.
\v 10 Neither be ye called Masters: for one is your Master, Christ.
\v 11 He that is the greater of you, shall be your servitor.
\v 12 And he that exalteth himself, shall be humbled: and he that humbleth himself, shall be exalted.
\v 13 But woe to you Scribes & Pharisees, hypocrites: because you shut the Kingdom of Heaven before men. For yourselves do not enter in: & those that are going in, you suffer not to enter.
\v 14 Woe to you Scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites: because you devour widows' houses, praying long prayers. For this you shall receive the greater judgement.
\v 15 Woe to you Scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites: because you go round about the sea and the land, to make one proselyte: and when he is made, you make him the child of hell double more than yourselves.
\v 16 Woe to you blind guides, that say, whosoever shall swear by the temple, it is nothing: but he that shall swear by the gold of the temple, is bound.
\v 17 Ye foolish and blind; for whether is greater, the gold, or the temple that sanctifieth the gold?
\v 18 And whosoever shall swear by the Altar, it is nothing: but whosoever shall swear by the gift that is upon it, is bound.
\v 19 Ye blind; for whether is greater, the gift, or the Altar that sanctifieth the gift?
\v 20 He therefore that sweareth by the Altar, sweareth by it, and by all things that are upon it:
\v 21 And whosoever shall swear by the temple, sweareth by it and by him that dwelleth in it:
\v 22 And he that sweareth by Heaven, sweareth by the throne of God, and by him that sitteth thereon.
\v 23 Woe to you Scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites: because you tithe mint, and anise, and cummin, and have left the weightier things of the law, judgement, and mercy, and faith. These things you ought to have done, & not to have omitted those.
\v 24 Blind guides, that strain a gnat, and swallow a camel.
\v 25 Woe to you Scribes and Pharisees, Hypocrites: because you make clean that on the outside of the cup and dish, but within you are full of rapine and uncleanness. \f + \fr 23:25 \ft they are full.\f*
\v 26 Thou blind Pharisee, first make clean the inside of the cup and the dish that the outside may become clean.
\v 27 Woe to you Scribes and Pharisees, Hypocrites: because you are like to whited sepulchres, which outwardly appear unto men beautiful, but within are full of dead men's bones, and all filthiness.
\v 28 So you also outwardly indeed appear to men just; but inwardly you are full of hypocrisy and iniquity.
\v 29 Woe to you Scribes and Pharisees, Hypocrites: because you build the Prophets' sepulchres, and garnish the monuments of just men,
\v 30 and say: If we had been in our fathers' days, we had not been their fellows in the blood of the Prophets.
\v 31 Therefore you are a testimony to your own selves, that you are the sons of them that killed the Prophets.
\v 32 And fill you up the measure of your fathers.
\v 33 You serpents, viper's broods, how will you flee from the judgement of Hell?
\v 34 Therefore behold I send unto you Prophets, and wise men, and Scribes, and of them you shall kill & crucify, and of them you shall scourge in your Synagogues, and persecute from city into city: \f + \fr 23:34 \ft The Gospel upon S. Steven's day Decemb. 26. And his Invention. Aug. 3.\f*
\v 35 that upon you may come all the just blood that was shed upon the earth, from the blood of Abel the just, even unto the blood of Zacharias the son of Barachias, whom you murdered between the temple & the altar.
\v 36 Amen I say to you, all these things shall come upon this generation.
\v 37 Jerusalem, Jerusalem, which killest the Prophets, and stonest them that were sent to thee, how often would I gather together thy children as the hen doth gather together her chickens under her wings, and thou wouldest not? \f + \fr 23:37 \ft Free will.\f*
\v 38 Behold, your house shall be left desert to you.
\v 39 For I say to you, you shall not see me from hence forth till you say: Blessed is he that cometh in the name of our Lord.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 \sc And Jesus\sc* being gone out of the temple, went. And his Disciples came to shew him the buildings of the temple.
\v 2 And he answering said to them: Do you see all these things? Amen I say to you, there shall not be left here a stone upon a stone that shall not be destroyed.
\v 3 And when he was sitting upon Mount-olivet, the Disciples came to him secretly, saying: Tell us, when shall these things be? and what shall be the sign of thy coming, and of the consummation of the world? \f + \fr 24:3 \ft The Gospel for a votive Mass in time of war, & for many Martyrs.\f*
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said to them: Beware that no man seduce you: \f + \fr 24:4 \ft TUESDAY night.\f*
\v 5 for many shall come in my name saying, I am Christ; and they shall seduce many.
\v 6 For you shall hear of wars, & bruits of wars. See that ye be not troubled. For these things must be done, but the end is not yet.
\v 7 For Nation shall rise against Nation, and Kingdom against Kingdom; and there shall be pestilences, and famines, and earth-quakes in places;
\v 8 and all these things are the beginnings of sorrows.
\v 9 Then shall they deliver you into tribulation, and shall kill you: and you shall be odious to all Nations for my name's sake.
\v 10 And then many shall be scandalized: and they shall deliver up one another: and they shall hate one another.
\v 11 And many false-prophets shall rise, and shall seduce many. \f + \fr 24:11 \ft There were in the people false Prophets, as among you also shall be lying Masters, which shall bring in Sects of perdition. 2. Pet. 2.\f*
\v 12 And because iniquity shall abound, the charity of many shall wax cold.
\v 13 But he that shall persevere to the end, he shall be saved.
\v 14 And this Gospel of the Kingdom shall be preached in the whole world, for a testimony to all nations, and then shall come the consummation.
\v 15 Therefore when you shall see \add the abomination of desolation,\add* which was spoken of by Daniel the Prophet, standing in the holy place (he that readeth, let him understand) \f + \fr 24:15 \ft The Gospel upon the last Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 16 then they that are in Jewry, let them flee to the mountains:
\v 17 and he that is on the house-top let him not come down to take any thing out of his house:
\v 18 and he that is in the field, let him not go back to take his coat.
\v 19 And woe to them that are with child, and that give suck in those days.
\v 20 But pray that your flight be not in the winter, or on the Sabboth,
\v 21 For there shall be then great tribulation, such as hath not been from the beginning of the world until now, neither shall be.
\v 22 And unless those days had been shortened, no flesh should be saved: but for the Elect the days shall be shortened.
\v 23 Then if any man shall say unto you: Lo here is Christ, or there; do not believe him. \f + \fr 24:23 \ft Whosoever draweth Christ or his Church from the Communion and fellowship of all Nations Christened, to one corner, town, or Country, believe him not. Aug. de unit. Ec. c. 3.\f*
\v 24 For there shall rise false Christs and false-Prophets, and shall shew great signs and wonders, so that the Elect also (if it be possible) may be induced into error.
\v 25 Lo I have foretold you.
\v 26 If therefore they shall say unto you: Behold he is in the desert; go ye not out: Behold in the closets, believe it not.
\v 27 For as lightning cometh out of the east, and appeareth even into the west, so shall also the advent of the Son of man be.
\v 28 Wheresoever the body is, thither shall the Eagles also be gathered together.
\v 29 And immediately after the tribulation of those days the sun shall be darkened, and the moon shall not give her light, and the stars shall fall from Heaven, and the powers of Heaven shall be moved:
\v 30 and then shall appear the sign of the Son of man in Heaven: and then shall all tribes of the earth bewail: and they shall see the Son of man coming in the clouds of Heaven with much power and majesty. \f + \fr 24:30 \ft This sign of the son of man, is the holy Cross, which then shall appear to the Jews to their confusion. Chrys. in Mat. ho. 77. It shall be no less confusion to Heretics that cannot abide the sign thereof.\f*
\v 31 And he shall send his Angels with a trumpet, and a great voice: and they shall gather together his Elect from the four winds, from the furthest parts of Heaven even to the ends thereof.
\v 32 And of the figtree learn a parable: When now the bough thereof is tender, and the leaves come forth, you know that summer is nigh.
\v 33 So you also, when you shall see these things, know ye that it is nigh even at the doors.
\v 34 Amen I say to you, that this generation shall not pass, till all these things be done.
\v 35 Heaven and earth shall pass, but my words shall not pass.
\v 36 But of that day and hour nobody knoweth, neither the Angels of Heaven, but the Father alone.
\v 37 And as in the days of Noe, so shall also the coming of the Son of man be.
\v 38 For as they were in the days before the flood, eating and drinking, marrying and giving to marriage, even unto that day in which Noe entered into the ark,
\v 39 and knew not till the flood came, & took them all: so also shall the coming of the Son of man be.
\v 40 Then two shall be in the field: one shall be taken, & one shall be left.
\v 41 Two women grinding in the mill: one shall be taken, & one shall be left.
\v 42 Watch therefore because you know not what hour your Lord will come.
\v 43 But this know ye, that if the good-man of the house did know what hour the thief would come, he would surely watch, and would not suffer his house to be broken up. \f + \fr 24:43 \ft The Gospel upon S. Clement martyr his day Novemb. 23. And for some Confessors Bishops.\f*
\v 44 Therefore be you also ready, because at what hour you know not, the Son of man will come.
\v 45 Who, thinkest thou, is a faithful and wise servant, whom his Lord hath appointed over his family, to give them meat in season?
\v 46 Blessed is that servant, whom when his Lord cometh, he shall find so doing.
\v 47 Amen I say to you, that over all his goods shall he appoint him.
\v 48 But if that naughty servant shall say in his heart: My Lord is long a coming:
\v 49 and shall begin to strike his fellow-servants, and eateth, & drinketh with drunkards:
\v 50 the Lord of that servant shall come in a day that he hopeth not, & an hour that he knoweth not,
\v 51 and shall divide him, & appoint his portion with the hypocrites: there shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 \sc Then\sc* shall the Kingdom of Heaven be like to ten virgins, which taking their lamps went forth to meet the bridegroom and the bride. \f + \fr 25:1 \ft The Gospel upon S. Catharine's day. Novemb. 25. And for some other holy Virgins.\f*
\v 2 And five of them were foolish, and five wise.
\v 3 But the five foolish, having taken their lamps, did not take oil with them:
\v 4 but the wise did take oil in their vessels with the lamps.
\v 5 And the bridegroom tarrying long they slumbered all and slept.
\v 6 And at midnight there was a clamour made: Behold the bridegroom cometh, go ye forth to meet him.
\v 7 Then arose all those virgins, and they trimmed their lamps.
\v 8 And the foolish said to the wise: Give us of your oil, because our lamps are going out. \f + \fr 25:8 \ft If we be not in the favour of God, and have not our own merits, we shall not be holpen by other men's deserts at the day of judgement.\f*
\v 9 The wise answered, saying: Lest peradventure there suffice not for us and you, go rather to them that sell, and buy for yourselves.
\v 10 And whiles they went to buy, the bridegroom was come: and they that were ready, entered with him to the marriage, and the gate was shut.
\v 11 But last of all come also the other virgins saying: Lord, Lord, open to us.
\v 12 But he answering said: Amen I say to you, I know you not.
\v 13 Watch ye therefore, because you know not the day nor the hour.
\v 14 For even as a man going into a strange country, called his servants, and delivered them his goods. \f + \fr 25:14 \ft The Gospel upon S. Nicolas' day Decemb. 6. and for some other Confessors Bishops.\f*
\v 15 And to one he gave five talents, and to another two, and to another one, to every one according to his proper faculty: and immediately he took his journey.
\v 16 And he that had received the five talents, went his way, and occupied with the same, and gained other five.
\v 17 Likewise also he that had received the two, gained other two.
\v 18 But he that had received the one, going his way digged into the earth, and hid his lord's money.
\v 19 But after much time the lord of those servants cometh, & made account with them.
\v 20 And there came he that had received the five talents, & offered other five talents, saying: Lord five talents thou didst deliver me, behold I have gained other five besides. \f + \fr 25:20 \ft Free will with God's grace doth merit.\f*
\v 21 His lord said unto him: Well-fare thee good and faithful servant, because thou hast been faithful over a few things, I will place thee over many things: enter into the joy of thy lord.
\v 22 And there came also he that had received the two talents, & said: Lord two talents thou didst deliver me: behold I have gained other two.
\v 23 His lord said to him: Well-fare thee good & faithful servant: because thou hast been faithful over a few things, I will place thee over many things, enter into the joy of thy lord.
\v 24 And he also that had received the one talent, came forth, and said: Lord, I know that thou art a hard man; thou reapest where thou didst not sow, and gatherest where thou strawedst not:
\v 25 and being afraid I went, and hid thy talent in the earth: behold lo here thou hast that which thine is.
\v 26 And his lord answering, said to him: Naughty and slothful servant, thou didst know that I reap where I sow not, & gather where I strawed not: \f + \fr 25:26 \ft Aterrible example for all such as do not employ the very least gift of God, to his glory.\f*
\v 27 thou oughtest therefore to have committed my money to the bankers, and coming I might have received mine own with usury.
\v 28 Take ye away therefore the talent from him, and give it him that hath ten talents.
\v 29 For to every one that hath shall be given, and he shall abound: but from him that hath not, that also which he seemeth to have, shall be taken away from him.
\v 30 And the unprofitable servant cast ye out into the utter darkness. There shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
\v 31 And when the Son of man shall come in his majesty, and all the Angels with him, then shall he sit upon the seat of his majesty: \f + \fr 25:31 \ft The Gospel upon Monday the first week of Lent.\f*
\v 32 and all nations shall be gathered together before him, and he shall separate them one from another, as the pastor separateth the sheep from the goats:
\v 33 and shall set the sheep at his right hand, but the goats at his left.
\v 34 Then shall the King say to them that shall be at his right hand: Come ye blessed of my Father, possess you the Kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world. \f + \fr 25:34 \ft This Kingdom then is prepared for those only that do good works: as Christ also signifieth elsewhere, saying that it is not in his power to give it otherwise. See the annot. c. 20. 23.\f*
\v 35 For I was an hungered, and you gave me to eat: I was a thirst, and you gave me to drink.
\v 36 I was a stranger, and you took me in: naked, and you covered me: sick, and you visited me. I was in prison, and you came to me.
\v 37 Then shall the just answer him, saying: Lord, when did we see thee an hungered, and fed thee, a thirst, and gave thee drink?
\v 38 and when did we see thee a stranger, and took thee in? Or naked, and covered thee?
\v 39 Or when did we see thee sick or in prison, and came to thee?
\v 40 And the King answering, shall say to them: Amen I say to you, as long as you did it to one of these my least brethren, you did it to me.
\v 41 Then he shall say to them also that shall be at his left hand: Get ye away from me you cursed into fire everlasting, which was prepared for the devil and his angels.
\v 42 For I was an hungered, & you gave me not to eat, I was a thirst, & you gave me not to drink.
\v 43 I was a stranger, and you took me not in: naked, and you covered me not: sick, & in prison, and you did not visit me.
\v 44 Then they also shall answer him, saying: Lord, when did we see thee an hungered, or a thirst, or a stranger, or naked, or sick, or in prison, & did not minister to thee?
\v 45 Then he shall answer them, saying, Amen I say to you, as long as you did it not to one of these lesser, neither did you it to me.
\v 46 And these shall go into punishment everlasting: but the just, into life everlasting.
\c 26
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass, when \sc Jesus\sc* had ended all these words, he said to his Disciples: \f + \fr 26:1 \ft The Passion according to S. Matthew in these two Chapters, is the Gospel at Mass upon Palm Sunday.\f*
\v 2 You know that after two days shall be Pasch, and the Son of man shall be delivered to be crucified.
\v 3 Then were gathered together the chief Priests and Ancients of the people into the court of the high Priest, who was called Caiphas: \f + \fr 26:3 \ft TENEBRÆ-Wednesday.\f*
\v 4 and they consulted how they might by some wile apprehend \sc Jesus\sc*, and kill him.
\v 5 But they said: Not on the festival day, lest perhaps there might be a tumult among the people.
\v 6 And when \sc Jesus\sc* was in Bethania in the house of Simon the Leper
\v 7 there came to him a woman having an alabaster-box of precious ointment, and poured it out upon his head as he sat at the table.
\v 8 And the Disciples seeing it, had indignation saying: Whereto is this waste?
\v 9 For this might have been sold for much, and given to the poor.
\v 10 And \sc Jesus\sc* knowing it, said to them: Why do you molest this woman? For she hath wrought a good work upon me.
\v 11 For the poor you have always with you: but me you have not always.
\v 12 For she in pouring this ointment upon my body hath done it to bury me.
\v 13 Amen I say to you, wheresoever this Gospel shall be preached in the whole world, that also which she hath done, shall be reported for a memory of her. \f + \fr 26:13 \ft Hereby we learn that the good works of Saints are to be recorded and set forth to their honour in the Church after their death. Whereof rise their holy days and Commemorations.\f*
\v 14 Then went one of the Twelve, which was called Judas Iscarioth, to the chief Priests,
\v 15 & said to them: What will you give me, and I will deliver him unto you? But they appointed unto him thirty pieces of silver.
\v 16 And from thenceforth he sought opportunity to betray him.
\v 17 And the first day of the Azymes the Disciples came to \sc Jesus\sc* saying: Where wilt thou that we prepare for thee to eat the Pasch? \f + \fr 26:17 \ft MAUNDY Thursday.\f*
\v 18 But \sc Jesus\sc* said: Go ye into the city to a certain man, and say to him: The Master saith, my time is at hand, with thee do I make the Pasch with my Disciples.
\v 19 And the Disciples did as \sc Jesus\sc* appointed them, and they prepared the Pasch.
\v 20 But when it was even, he sat down with his twelve Disciples.
\v 21 And while they were eating, he said: Amen I say to you, that one of you shall betray me.
\v 22 And they being very sad, began every one to say: Is it I Lord?
\v 23 But he answering said: He that dippeth his hand with me in the dish, he shall betray me.
\v 24 The Son of man indeed goeth as it is written of him: but woe be to that man, by whom the Son of man shall be betrayed. It were good for him, if that man had not been born.
\v 25 And Judas that betrayed him, answering said: Is it I Rabbi? He saith to him: Thou hast said.
\v 26 And whiles they were at supper, \sc Jesus\sc* took bread, and blessed, and brake: and he gave to his Disciples, and said: Take ye, and eat: \sc This is my Body\sc*.
\v 27 And taking the chalice, he gave thanks: and gave to them, saying: Drink ye all of this. \f + \fr 26:27 \ft See the margent note Mar. 14, 23.\f*
\v 28 \sc For This is my Blood of The New Testament, Which Shall be Shed For Many Unto Remission of Sins\sc*.
\v 29 And I say to you, I will not drink from henceforth of this fruit of the vine, until that day when I shall drink it with you new in the Kingdom of my Father.
\v 30 And an hymn being said, they went forth unto Mount-olivet. \f + \fr 26:30 \ft THURSDAY night.\f*
\v 31 Then \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: All you shall be scandalized in me in this night. For it is written: \add I will strike the Pastor, and the sheep of the flock shall be dispersed.\add* \f + \fr 26:31 \ft The Nocturne of Matins in the Church's service, answereth to this night part of our Saviour's Passion, and so consequently the other Canonical hours to the rest.\f*
\v 32 But after I shall be risen again, I will go before you into Galilee.
\v 33 And Peter answering, said to him: Although all shall be scandalized in thee, I will never be scandalized.
\v 34 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Amen I say to thee, that in this night before the cock crow, thou shalt deny me thrice.
\v 35 Peter saith to him: Yea though I should die with thee, I will not deny thee. Likewise also said all the Disciples.
\v 36 Then \sc Jesus\sc* cometh with them into a village called Gethsemani: and he said to his Disciples: Sit you here till I go yonder, and pray.
\v 37 And taking to him Peter and the two sons of Zebedee, he began to wax sorrowful and to be sad.
\v 38 Then he saith to them: My soul is sorrowful even unto death: stay here, and watch with me.
\v 39 And being gone forward a little, he fell upon his face, praying, and saying: My Father, if it be possible, let this chalice pass from me. Nevertheless not as I will, but as thou.
\v 40 And he cometh to his Disciples, and findeth them sleeping, and he saith to Peter: Even so? Could you not watch one hour with me?
\v 41 Watch ye, & pray that ye enter not into tentation. The Spirit indeed is prompt, but the flesh weak.
\v 42 Again the second time he went, and prayed, saying: My Father, if this chalice may not pass, but I must drink it, thy will be done.
\v 43 And he cometh again, and findeth them sleeping, for their eyes were become heavy.
\v 44 And leaving them, he went again: and he prayed the third time, saying the selfsame word.
\v 45 Then he cometh to his Disciples, and saith to them: Sleep ye now and take rest. Behold the hour approacheth, and the Son of man shall be betrayed into the hands of sinners.
\v 46 Rise, let us go: behold he approacheth that shall betray me.
\v 47 As he yet spake, behold Judas one of the Twelve came, and with him a great multitude with swords and clubs, sent from the chief Priests and the ancients of the people.
\v 48 And he that betrayed him, gave them a sign, saying: Whomsoever I shall kiss, that is he, hold him.
\v 49 And forthwith coming to \sc Jesus\sc*, he said: Hail Rabbi. And he kissed him.
\v 50 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Friend, whereto art thou come? Then they drew near, and laid hands on \sc Jesus\sc*, and held him.
\v 51 And behold one of them that were with \sc Jesus\sc*, stretching forth his hand, drew out his sword; and striking the servant of the high Priest, cut off his ear.
\v 52 Then \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Return thy sword into his place: for all that take the sword shall perish with the sword.
\v 53 Thinkest thou that I cannot ask my Father, and he will give me presently more than twelve legions of Angels?
\v 54 How then shall the scriptures be fulfilled, that so it must be done?
\v 55 In that hour \sc Jesus\sc* said to the multitudes: You are come out as it were to a thief with swords and clubs to apprehend me. I sat daily with you teaching in the temple, and you laid no hands on me.
\v 56 And all this was done, that the scriptures of the Prophets might be fulfilled. Then the Disciples all leaving him, fled.
\v 57 But they taking hold of \sc Jesus\sc*, led him to Caiphas the high Priest, where the Scribes and ancients were assembled.
\v 58 And Peter followed him a far off, even to the court of the high Priest. And going in he sat with the servants, that he might see the end.
\v 59 And the chief Priests and the whole Council sought false witness against \sc Jesus\sc*, that they might put him to death:
\v 60 and they found not, whereas many false witnesses had come in. And last of all there came two false witnesses;
\v 61 and they said: This man said, I am able to destroy the temple of God, and after three days to re-edify it.
\v 62 And the high Priest rising up, said to him: Answerest thou nothing to the things which these do testify against thee?
\v 63 But \sc Jesus\sc* held his peace. And the high Priest said to him: I adjure thee by the living God, that thou tell us if thou be Christ the Son of God.
\v 64 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Thou hast said. Nevertheless I say to you, hereafter you shall see the Son of man sitting on the right hand of the power of God, and coming in the clouds of Heaven.
\v 65 Then the high Priest rent his garments, saying: He hath blasphemed, what need we witnesses any further? Behold, now you have heard the blasphemy;
\v 66 how think you? But they answering said: He is guilty of death.
\v 67 Then did they spit on his face, and buffeted him, & other smote his face with the palms of their hands,
\v 68 saying: Prophesy unto us O Christ; who is he that strook thee?
\v 69 But Peter sat without in the court; and there came to him one wench, saying: Thou also wast with \sc Jesus\sc* the Galilean.
\v 70 But he denied before them all, saying: I wot not what thou sayest.
\v 71 And as he went out of the gate, another wench saw him, and she saith to them that were there: And this fellow also was with \sc Jesus\sc* the Nazarite.
\v 72 And again he denied with an oath: That I know not the man.
\v 73 And after a little they came that stood by, and said to Peter: Surely thou also art of them: for even thy speech doth bewray thee.
\v 74 Then he began to curse and to swear that he knew not the man. And incontinent the cock crew. \f + \fr 26:74 \ft To this time the LAUDS do answer in the Church's service.\f*
\v 75 And Peter remembered the word of \sc Jesus\sc* which he had said: Before the cock crow, thou shalt deny me thrice. And going forth, he wept bitterly.
\c 27
\p
\v 0 being buried, they to make all sure, set soldiers to keep \add his sepulcher.\add*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when morning was come; all the chief Priests and ancients of the people consulted together against \sc Jesus\sc*, that they might put him to death. \f + \fr 27:1 \ft PRIME, or Hora prima, in the Church's Service.\f*
\v 2 And they brought him bound and delivered him to Ponce Pilate the President. \f + \fr 27:2 \ft GOOD FRIDAY.\f*
\v 3 Then Judas that betrayed him, seeing that he was condemned, repenting him, returned the thirty silver pieces to the chief Priests and ancients,
\v 4 saying: I have sinned, betraying just blood. But they said: What is that to us? look thou to it.
\v 5 And casting down the silver pieces in the temple, he departed: and went and hanged himself with an halter.
\v 6 And the chief Priests having taken the silver pieces, said: It is not lawful to cast them into the Corbana, because it is the price of blood. \f + \fr 27:6 \ft This Corbana was a place about the Temple, which received the people's gifts or offerings. See Mar. 12, v. 42.\f*
\v 7 And after they had consulted together, they bought with them the potter's field, to be a burying place for strangers.
\v 8 For this cause that field was called \add Haceldama,\add* that is, \add the field of blood,\add* even to this present day.
\v 9 Then was fulfilled that which was spoken by Jeremie the Prophet, saying: \add And they took the thirty pieces of silver, the price of the priced, whom they did price of the children of Israel.\add*
\v 10 \add And they gave them into the potter's field, as our Lord did appoint to me.\add*
\v 11 And \sc Jesus\sc* stood before the President, and the President asked him, saying: Art thou the King of the Jews? \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Thou sayest.
\v 12 And when he was accused of the chief Priests and Ancients, he answered nothing.
\v 13 Then Pilate saith to him: Doest thou not hear how many testimonies they allege against thee?
\v 14 And he answered him not to any word: so that the President did marvel exceedingly.
\v 15 And upon the solemn day the President had accustomed to release unto the People one prisoner, whom they would. \f + \fr 27:15 \ft HORA TERTIA in the Church's Service.\f*
\v 16 And he had then a notorious prisoner, that was called Barabbas.
\v 17 They therefore being gathered together, Pilate said: Whom will you that I release to you, Barabbas, or \sc Jesus\sc* that is called Christ?
\v 18 For he knew that for envy they had delivered him.
\v 19 And as he was sitting in place of judgement, his wife sent unto him, saying: Have thou nothing to do with that just man. For I have suffered many things this day in my sleep for him.
\v 20 But the chief Priests and ancients persuaded the people, that they should ask Barabbas, and make \sc Jesus\sc* away.
\v 21 And the President answering, said to them: Whether will you of the two to be released unto you? But they said, Barabbas.
\v 22 Pilate saith to them: What shall I do then with \sc Jesus\sc* that is called Christ? They say all: Let him be crucified.
\v 23 The President said to them: Why what evil hath he done? But they cried the more, saying: Let him be crucified.
\v 24 And Pilate seeing that he nothing prevailed, but rather tumult was toward; taking water he washed his hands before the People, saying: I am innocent of the blood of this just man: look you to it.
\v 25 And the whole people answering, said: His blood be upon us, and upon our children.
\v 26 Then he released to them Barabbas, and having scourged \sc Jesus\sc*, delivered him unto them for to be crucified.
\v 27 Then the President's soldiers taking \sc Jesus\sc* into the Palace, gathered together unto him the whole band:
\v 28 and stripping him, put a scarlet cloak about him.
\v 29 and platting a crown of thorns, put it upon his head, and a reed in his right hand. And bowing the knee before him, they mocked him, saying: Hail King of the Jews.
\v 30 And spitting upon him, they took the reed, and smote his head.
\v 31 And after they had mocked him, they took off the cloak from him, and put on him his own garments, and led him away to crucify him.
\v 32 And in going they found a man of Cyrene, named Simon: him they forced to take up his Cross.
\v 33 And they came into the place that is called Golgotha, which is, the place of Calvary. \f + \fr 27:33 \ft HORA SEXTA in the Church's Service.\f*
\v 34 And they gave him wine to drink mingled with gall. And when he had tasted, he would not drink.
\v 35 And after they had crucified him; they divided his garments, casting lots; that it might be fulfilled which was spoken by the Prophet, saying: \add They divided my garments among them; and upon my vesture they did cast lots.\add*
\v 36 And they sat and watched him.
\v 37 And they put over his head his cause written: \sc This is Jesus The King of The Jews\sc*.
\v 38 Then were crucified with him two thieves; one on the right hand, and one on the left.
\v 39 And they that passed by, blasphemed him, wagging their heads,
\v 40 and saying: Vah, thou that destroyest the Temple of God and in three days doest re-edify it; save thine own self: if thou be the Son of God, come down from the Cross.
\v 41 In like manner also the chief Priests with the Scribes and ancients mocking, said:
\v 42 He saved other; himself he cannot save: if he be the King of Israel, let him now come down from the Cross, and we will believe him.
\v 43 He trusted in God; let him now deliver him if he will: for he said, that I am the Son of God.
\v 44 And the self same thing the thieves also that were crucified with him, reproached him withal.
\v 45 And from the sixth hour, there was darkness made upon the whole earth, until the ninth hour.
\v 46 And about the ninth hour \sc Jesus\sc* cried with a mighty voice, saying: \add Eli, Eli, lamma-sabacthani?\add* that is, \add My God, my God, why hast thou forsaken me?\add*
\v 47 And certain that stood there and heard, said: He calleth Elias.
\v 48 And incontinent one of them running, took a sponge, & filled it with vinegar; and put it on a reed, and gave him to drink.
\v 49 And other said: Let be, let us see whether Elias come to deliver him.
\v 50 And \sc Jesus\sc* again crying with a mighty voice, yielded up the ghost.
\v 51 And behold the veil of the Temple was rent in two pieces, from the top even to the bottom, and the earth did quake, and the rocks were rent, \f + \fr 27:51 \ft HORA NONA in the Church's Service.\f*
\v 52 And the graves were opened: and many bodies of the saints that had slept, rose.
\v 53 And they going forth out of the graves after his resurrection, came into the holy city; and appeared to many.
\v 54 And the Centurion and they that were with him watching \sc Jesus\sc*, having seen the earth-quake and the things that were done, were sore afraid, saying: Indeed this was the Son of God.
\v 55 And there were there many women a far off, which had followed \sc Jesus\sc* from Galilee, ministering unto him:
\v 56 among whom was Mary Magdalene, and Mary the mother of James and Joseph, and the mother of the Sons of Zebedee.
\v 57 And when it was evening, there came a certain rich man of Arimathæa, named Joseph, who also himself was disciple to \sc Jesus\sc*. \f + \fr 27:57 \ft HORA VESPERARUM, or, Evensong.\f*
\v 58 He went to Pilate, and asked the body of \sc Jesus\sc*. Then Pilate commanded that the body should be delivered.
\v 59 And Joseph taking the body, wrapt it in clean sindon, \f + \fr 27:59 \ft HORA COMPLETORII, or, Compline.\f*
\v 60 & laid it in his own new monument, which he had hewed out in a rock. And he rolled a great stone to the door of the monument, & went his way.
\v 61 And there was there Mary Magdalene, & the other Mary, sitting over against the sepulchre.
\v 62 And the next day, which is after the Parasceve, the chief Priests and the Pharisees came together to Pilate, \f + \fr 27:62 \ft SATURDAY called Sabbatum sanctum.\f*
\v 63 saying: Sir, we have remembered, that that seducer said yet living, After three days I will rise again.
\v 64 Command therefore the sepulchre to be kept until the third day; lest perhaps his Disciples come, and steal him, & say to the people, he is risen from the dead: and the last error shall be worse than the first.
\v 65 Pilate said to them: You have a guard: go, guard it as you know.
\v 66 And they departing, made the sepulchre sure; sealing up the stone, with watchmen.
\c 28
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* in the evening of the Sabboth which dawneth on the first of the Sabboth, came Mary Magdalene, and the other Mary to see the sepulchre. \f + \fr 28:1 \ft The Gospel for the night Mass of Christ's Resurrection, which is now used to be said on Easter eve.\f* \f + \fr 28:1 \ft EASTER day.\f*
\v 2 And behold there was made a great earth-quake. For an Angel of our Lord descended from Heaven: and coming, rolled back the stone, and sat upon it:
\v 3 and his countenance was as lightning, and his garment as snow.
\v 4 And for fear of him, the watchmen were frighted, and became as dead.
\v 5 And the Angel answering said to the women: Fear not you. For I know that you seek \sc Jesus\sc* that was crucified.
\v 6 He is not here, for he is risen, as he said. Come, and see the place where our Lord was laid.
\v 7 And going quickly, tell ye his Disciples that he is risen: and behold he goeth before you into Galilee: there you shall see him. Lo I have foretold you.
\v 8 And they went forth quickly out of the monument with fear and great joy, running to tell his Disciples.
\v 9 And behold \sc Jesus\sc* met them, saying: All hail. But they came near and took hold of his feet, and adored him.
\v 10 Then \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Fear not. Go, tell my brethren that they go into Galilee, there they shall see me.
\v 11 Who when they were departed, behold certain of the watchmen came into the city, and told the chief Priests all things that had been done.
\v 12 And being assembled together with the Ancients, taking counsel, they gave a great sum of money to the soldiers,
\v 13 saying: Say you, that his Disciples came by night, and stole him away when we were asleep.
\v 14 And if the President shall hear of this, we will persuade him, and make you secure.
\v 15 But they taking the money, did as they were taught. And this word was bruited abroad among the Jews, even unto this day.
\v 16 And the eleven Disciples went into Galilee, unto the mount where \sc Jesus\sc* had appointed them. \f + \fr 28:16 \ft The Gospel upon Friday in Easter week.\f*
\v 17 And seeing him they adored, but some doubted.
\v 18 And \sc Jesus\sc* coming near spake unto them, saying: All power is given to me in Heaven and in earth. \f + \fr 28:18 \ft The Gospel in the feast of the B. Trinity.\f*
\v 19 going therefore teach ye all Nations: \sc Baptizing Them in The Name of The Father, And of The Son, And of The Holy Ghost\sc*,
\v 20 teaching them to observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you: and behold I am with you all days, even to the consummation of the world.
